17 NEEDS-BASED PUBLIC SCHOOL CAPITAL PROGRAM CHANGES
18 SECTION 4.3A.(a) Article 38B of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes reads as
19 rewritten:
20 "Article 38B.
21 "Needs-Based Public School Capital Fund.
22 "§ 115C-546.10. Fund created; purpose; prioritization.
23 There is created the Needs-Based Public School Capital Fund as an interest-bearing,
24 nonreverting special fund in the Department of Public Instruction. The State Treasurer shall be
25 the custodian of the Needs-Based Public School Capital Fund and shall invest its assets in
26 accordance with the provisions of G.S. 147-69.2 and G.S. 147-69.3. The Department of Public
27 Instruction shall award grants from the Fund to counties to assist with their critical public school
28 building capital needs in accordance with the following priorities:
29 (1) Counties designated as development tier one areas.
30 (2) Counties with greater need and less ability to generate sales tax and property
31 tax revenue.
32 (3) Counties with a high debt-to-tax revenue ratio.
33 (4) The extent to which a project will address critical deficiencies in adequately
34 serving the current and future student population.
35 (5) Projects with new construction or complete renovation of existing facilities.
36 (6) Projects that will consolidate two or more schools into one new facility.
37 (7) Counties that have not received a grant under this Article in the previous three
38 years.
39 (8) Whether the county has declined or forfeited a previous grant awarded under
40 this Article.
41 (9) Whether the county has submitted a certification of intent to provide funding
42 necessary for project completion.
43 "§ 115C-546.11. Matching requirement; use of funds; maximum awards; project
44 review.project review; application time lines.
45 (a) An eligible county awarded a grant under this Article shall provide local matching
46 funds from county funds, other non-State funds, or a combination of these sources for the grant
47 as provided in this section. An eligible county is a county with an adjusted market value of taxable
48 real property of less than forty billion dollars ($40,000,000,000). The adjusted market value of
49 taxable property in a county is equal to the county's assessed taxable real property value, using
50 the latest available data published by the Department of Revenue, divided by the county's sales
51 assessment ratio determined under G.S. 105-289(h). The amount of matching funds for a county
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 awarded a grant shall be published annually by the Department of Public Instruction prior to any
2 application period. The local match requirement applied to the project shall be based on the match
3 requirement effective at the time of the grant award. The local match requirement is calculated
4 as follows:
5 Adjusted Market Value of Taxable Real Property
6
7 Over Up to Percentage Match
8 $0 $2 billion 0%
9 $2 billion $10 billion 5%
10 $10 billion $20 billion 15%
11 $20 billion $30 billion 25%
12 $30 billion $40 billion 35%
13 (b) Grant funds shall be used only for the construction of new school buildings and
14 additions, repairs, and renovations. Grant funds shall not be used for real property acquisition or
15 for capital improvements to administrative buildings. Grant funds shall be disbursed in a series
16 of payments based on the progress of the project. To obtain a payment, the grantee shall submit
17 a request for payment along with documentation of the expenditures for which the payment is
18 requested and evidence that the matching requirement contained in subsection (a) of this section
19 has been met. No portion of grant funds may be used to acquire a Leadership in Energy and
20 Environmental Design (LEED) certification.
21 (c) Maximum grant award amounts shall be determined as follows:
22 (1) Up to forty-two million dollars ($42,000,000) for an elementary school.
23 (2) Up to fifty-two million dollars ($52,000,000) for a middle school or a
24 combination of an elementary and middle school.
25 (3) Up to sixty-two million dollars ($62,000,000) for a high school.
26 (d) The Department of Public Instruction shall review projected enrollment to evaluate
27 the reasonableness of a project's size and scope. A county may include in a grant application a
28 minimum grant amount that would enable the project to proceed. A grant application that
29 proposes to consolidate two or more schools by (i) making additions or renovations at one or
30 more school facilities and (ii) closing one or more existing school facilities may be submitted
31 and considered by the Department of Public Instruction as a single project. Each application for
32 a grant under this Article shall be evaluated independent of other grant applications submitted. A
33 county may not apply for projects that exceed an aggregate amount greater than the maximum
34 grant award amounts listed in subsection (c) of this section in any single year. The Department
35 of Public Instruction shall not award a grant to an applicant at less than the requested amount or
36 less than the maximum grant amounts listed in subsection (c) of this section for the purpose of
37 reserving the amount of grant funds available for other grant applications. If a county declines or
38 otherwise forfeits a grant awarded under this section, the Department shall not award additional
39 grants to that county for 24 months from the date the grant award was declined or forfeited.
40 (e) No later than October 1 of each year, the Department of Public Instruction shall
41 publish the application requirements, including the applicable county match requirements
42 calculated pursuant to subsection (a) of this section, for grant awards under this Article to be
43 considered for the following fiscal year. The Department of Public Instruction shall open the
44 grant application period on January 1 of each year and shall accept grant applications meeting
45 the criteria established under this Article from that date until March 15 of each year. During the
46 grant application period, the Department of Public Instruction may work with applicants to
47 supplement grant applications with any information needed to evaluate the grant application.
48 Upon the closing of the grant application period on March 15 of each year, the Department shall
49 evaluate all applications received during the grant application period and, no later than May 1 of
50 each year, shall submit an unranked list of grant applications, to include a technical evaluation
51 and a statement of comparison to the priorities listed in G.S. 115C-546.10 for each application,
