1 that qualify under the conditions imposed by this Article to the chairs of the Senate Committee
2 on Appropriations/Base Budget, the chairs of the House Appropriations Committee, and the
3 Fiscal Research Division.
4 "§ 115C-546.12. Grant agreement; requirements.
5 (a) A county receiving grant funds pursuant to this Article shall enter into an agreement
6 with the Department of Public Instruction detailing the use of grant funds. The agreement shall
7 contain at least all of the following:
8 (1) A requirement that the grantee seek planning assistance and plan review from
9 the School Planning Section of the Department of Public Instruction.
10 (2) A progress payment provision governing disbursements to the county for the
11 duration of the school construction project based upon the construction
12 progress and documentation satisfactory to the Department that the matching
13 requirement in G.S. 115C-546.11 has been met.
14 (3) A provision requiring periodic reports to the Department of Public Instruction
15 on the use of disbursed grant funds and the progress of the school construction
16 project.
17 (4) A requirement that matching funds paid by the county pursuant to
18 G.S. 115C-546.11 must be derived from non-State and nonfederal funds.
19 (5) A provision requiring repayment in full of awarded grant funds in the event
20 the grant recipient declines the grant award or the grant is forfeited.
21 (b) Project construction must be initiated within 24 months of the award of grant funds.
22 The Superintendent of Public Instruction may grant a 12-month extension under extraordinary
23 circumstances.
24 (c) A grant awarded under this section may be forfeited if any of the following occur:
25 (1) Project construction is not initiated on time.
26 (2) Project scope changes significantly from what was outlined in the grant
27 agreement.
28 (3) Any statement or information provided in the grant application is later
29 determined to be materially false.
30 (4) Local funding is subsequently decreased from the amount provided in the
31 grant application.
32 (d) For grant awards that, due to extraordinary circumstances, are forfeited or declined,
33 the Department of Public Instruction may deduct reasonable administrative costs incurred by the
34 grant recipient in connection with the project from grant funds disbursed to the grant recipient in
35 the calculation of fund repayment. A grant recipient shall provide documentation satisfactory to
36 the Department to support any administrative costs to be deducted.
37 "§ 115C-546.13. Lease exception; requirements.
38 (a) Notwithstanding any provision of this Article to the contrary, a county may utilize
39 grant funds for a lease agreement if all of the following criteria are met:
40 (1) Ownership of the subject property on which the leased school is constructed
41 shall be retained by the county.
42 (2) The lease agreement shall include a repairs and maintenance provision that
43 requires the landlord to bear the entire expense of all repairs, maintenance,
44 alterations, or improvements to the basic structure, fixtures, appurtenances,
45 and grounds of the subject property for the term of the lease.
46 (3) The lease agreement shall be for a term of at least 15 years and no more than
47 25 years.
48 (4) In lieu of the progress payment requirement provided in G.S. 115C-546.11(b),
49 a county that has entered into a lease agreement shall provide a copy of the
50 lease agreement to the Department of Public Instruction and shall be
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 periodically reimbursed upon submission of documentation satisfactory to the
2 Department that the matching requirement of this section has been met.
3 (b) For the purposes of this section, the term "lease agreement" shall include any ancillary
4 agreements or predevelopment agreements entered into in anticipation of or in accordance with
5 a lease. A lease agreement entered into pursuant to this subsection shall be subject to the
6 requirements of Article 8 of Chapter 159 of the General Statutes. In determining whether the
7 lease agreement is necessary or expedient pursuant to G.S. 159-151(a)(1) and
8 G.S. 159-151(b)(1), the Local Government Commission may consider any other relevant
9 construction and financing methods available to the county.
10 "§ 115C-546.14. Reporting.
11 (a) On or before April 1 of each year, a grant recipient shall submit to the Department of
12 Public Instruction an annual report for the preceding year that describes the progress of the
13 project for which the grant was received. The grant recipient shall submit a final report to the
14 Department of Public Instruction within three months of the completion of the project.
15 (b) On or before May 1 of each year, the Department of Public Instruction shall submit a
16 report to the chairs of the Senate Appropriations Committee on Education/Higher Education, the
17 chairs of the House Appropriations Committee on Education, and the Fiscal Research Division.
18 The report shall contain at least all of the following information for the fiscal year:
19 (1) Number, description, and geographic distribution of projects awarded.project
20 applications received.
21 (2) Total cost of each project and amount supported by the Needs-Based Public
22 School Capital Fund.
23 (3) Projections for local school administrative unit capital needs for the next 30
24 years based upon present conditions and estimated demographic changes.
25 (4) Any legislative recommendations for improving the Needs-Based Public
26 School Capital Fund program."
