33 PROVIDE SOCIAL MEDIA PROTECTIONS FOR MINORS UNDER SIXTEEN YEARS
34 OF AGE
35 SECTION 5.13.(a) The General Statutes are amended by adding a new Chapter to
36 read:
37 "Chapter 114B.
38 "Social Media Protections for Minors.
39 "§ 114B-1. Title; definitions.
40 (a) Title. – This Chapter shall be known and may be cited as the "Social Media Protection
41 for Minors Act."
42 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
43 (1) Account holder. – A person who opens an account or creates a profile or is
44 identified by the social media platform by a unique identifier while using or
45 accessing a social media platform when the social media platform knows or
46 has reason to believe the person is a resident of this State.
47 (2) Anonymous age verification. – A commercially reasonable method used by a
48 government agency or a business for the purpose of age verification, that is
49 conducted by a nongovernmental, independent third party organized under the
50 laws of a state of the United States that meets all of the following criteria:
51 a. Has its principal place of business in a state of the United States.
Page 44 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. Is not owned or controlled by a company formed in a foreign country,
2 a government of a foreign country, or any other entity formed in a
3 foreign country.
4 (3) Daily active users. – The number of unique users in the United States who
5 used the online forum, website, or application at least eighty percent (80%) of
6 the days during the previous 12 months or, if the online forum, website, or
7 application did not exist during the previous 12 months, the number of unique
8 users in the United States who used the online forum, website, or application
9 at least eighty percent (80%) of the days during the previous month.
10 (4) Department. – The North Carolina Department of Justice.
11 (5) Minor. – A person who is under 16 years of age.
12 (6) Resident. – A person who lives in this State for more than six months of the
13 year.
14 (7) Social media platform or platform. – An online forum, website, or application
15 that satisfies all of the following criteria:
16 a. Allows users to upload content or view the content or activity of other
17 users.
18 b. Ten percent (10%) or more of the daily active users who are younger
19 than 16 years of age spend on average two hours per day or longer on
20 the online forum, website, or application on the days when using the
21 online forum, website, or application during the previous 12 months
22 or, if the online forum, website, or application did not exist during the
23 previous 12 months, during the previous month.
24 c. Employs algorithms that analyze user data or information on users to
25 select content for users.
26 d. Has any of the following addictive features:
27 1. Infinite scrolling, which means either (i) continuously loading
28 content or content that loads as the user scrolls down the page
29 without the need to open a separate page or (ii) seamless
30 content or the use of pages with no visible or apparent end or
31 page breaks.
32 2. Push notifications or alerts sent by the online forum, website,
33 or application to inform a user about specific activities or
34 events related to the user's account.
35 3. Displays personal interactive metrics that indicate the number
36 of times other users have clicked a button to indicate their
37 reaction to content or have shared or reposted the content.
38 4. Auto-play video or video that begins to play without the user
39 first clicking on the video or on a play button for that video.
40 5. Live-streaming or a function that allows a user or advertiser to
41 broadcast live video content in real time.
42 The term does not include (i) an online service, website, or application where
43 the exclusive function is email or direct messaging consisting of text,
44 photographs, pictures, images, or videos shared only between the sender and
45 the recipients, without displaying or posting publicly or to other users not
46 specifically identified as the recipients by the sender, (ii) an online service,
47 website, or application that consists primarily of news, sports, entertainment,
48 or other information or content that is not user generated but preselected by
49 the provider, and for which any chat, comments, or interactive functionality is
50 incidental to, directly related to, or dependent on the provision of such content,
51 (iii) a community forum where the primary purpose of the forum is for
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 45

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 customer self-service support related to products, sellers, services, events, or
2 places, or any combination thereof, (iv) an interactive video game service
3 equipped with parental controls, (v) online shopping, or (vi) e-commerce.
4 (8) Standard age verification. – Any commercially reasonable method of age
5 verification approved by the social media platform.
6 "§ 114B-2. Social media protections for minors.
7 (a) Minors Under 14 Years of Age. – A social media platform shall prohibit a minor who
8 is younger than 14 years of age from entering into a contract with the platform to become an
9 account holder and shall do all of the following:
10 (1) Terminate any account held by a minor under 14 years of age upon 30 days'
11 notice to the account holder. Termination must be effective upon the
12 expiration of the 30 days if the account holder fails to effectively dispute the
13 termination.
14 (2) Permanently delete all personal information held by the social media platform
15 relating to the terminated account, unless there are legal requirements to
16 maintain the information.
17 (b) Minors 14 or 15 Years of Age. – A social media platform shall prohibit a minor who
18 is 14 or 15 years of age from entering into a contract with the platform to become an account
19 holder unless the minor's parent or guardian provides consent for the minor to become an account
20 holder and shall do all of the following:
21 (1) Terminate any account held by an account holder who is 14 or 15 years of age
22 if the account holder's parent or guardian has not provided consent for the
23 minor to create or maintain the account. The social media platform shall
24 provide 30 days for an account holder to dispute the termination.
25 (2) Allow the parent or guardian of an account holder who is 14 or 15 years of
26 age to request that the minor's account be terminated. Termination must be
27 effective within 10 business days after the request.
28 (3) Permanently delete all personal information held by the social media platform
29 relating to the terminated account unless there are legal requirements to
30 maintain the information.
31 (c) Violations. – If the Department has reason to believe that a social media platform is
32 in violation of this section, the Department, as the enforcing entity, may bring an action against
33 the platform for an unfair or deceptive act or practice.
34 Any knowing or reckless violation of this section is deemed an unfair and deceptive trade
35 practice actionable under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes actionable solely by the Department
36 against a social media platform.
37 In addition to other remedies allowed by law, the Department may collect a civil penalty of
38 up to fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) per violation and reasonable attorneys' fees and court costs.
39 When the social media platform's failure to comply with this section is a consistent pattern of
40 knowing or reckless conduct, punitive damages may be assessed against the platform.
41 A social media platform that knowingly or recklessly violates this section is liable to the
42 minor account holder, including court costs and reasonable attorneys' fees. Claimants may be
43 awarded up to ten thousand dollars ($10,000) in damages. Any action brought under this
44 paragraph may only be brought on behalf of a minor account holder. A civil action for a claim
45 under this paragraph must be brought within one year from the date the complainant knew, or
46 reasonably should have known, of the alleged violation.
47 If a social media platform allows an account holder to use the social media platform, the
48 parties have entered into a contract.
49 This section does not preclude any other available remedy at law or in equity.
50 For purposes of bringing an action under this section, a social media platform that allows a
51 minor to create an account on the platform is considered to be both engaged in substantial and
Page 46 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 not isolated activities within this State and operating, conducting, engaging in, or carrying on a
2 business and doing business in this State, and is therefore subject to the jurisdiction of the courts
3 of this State.
4 (d) Enforcement. – If, by its own inquiry or as a result of complaints, the Department has
5 reason to believe that an entity or person has engaged in, or is engaging in, an act or practice that
6 violates this section, the Department may administer oaths and affirmations, subpoena witnesses
7 or matter, and collect evidence. Within five days, excluding weekends and legal holidays, after
8 the service of a subpoena or at any time before the return date specified therein, whichever is
9 longer, the party served may file in the superior court in the county in which it resides or in which
10 it transacts business and serve upon the enforcing authority a petition for an order modifying or
11 setting aside the subpoena. The petitioner may raise any objection or privilege which would be
12 available upon service of such subpoena in a civil action. The subpoena shall inform the party
13 served of its rights under this subsection.
14 If the matter that the Department seeks to obtain by subpoena is located outside the State, the
15 entity or person subpoenaed may make it available to the Department or its representative to
16 examine the matter at the place where it is located. The Department may designate
17 representatives, including officials of the state in which the matter is located, to inspect the matter
18 on its behalf, and may respond to similar requests from officials of other states.
19 Upon failure of an entity or person without lawful excuse to obey a subpoena and upon
20 reasonable notice to all persons affected, the Department may apply to the superior court for an
21 order compelling compliance.
22 The Department may request that an entity or person that refuses to comply with a subpoena
23 on the ground that testimony or matter may incriminate the entity or person be ordered by the
24 court to provide the testimony or matter. Except in a prosecution for perjury, an entity or
25 individual that complies with a court order to provide testimony or matter after asserting a valid
26 privilege against self-incrimination shall not have the testimony or matter so provided, or
27 evidence derived therefrom, received against the entity or person in any criminal investigation or
28 proceeding.
29 Any entity or person upon whom a subpoena is served pursuant to this subsection shall
30 comply with the terms thereof unless otherwise provided by order of the court.
31 Any entity or person that fails to appear with the intent to avoid, evade, or prevent compliance
32 in whole or in part with any investigation under this Chapter or who removes from any place,
33 conceals, withholds, mutilates, alters, or destroys, or by any other means falsifies any
34 documentary material in the possession, custody, or control of any entity or person subject to any
35 such subpoena, or knowingly conceals any relevant information with the intent to avoid, evade,
36 or prevent compliance shall be liable for a civil penalty of not more than five thousand dollars
37 ($5,000) per week in violation, reasonable attorneys' fees, and costs.
38 (e) Rules. – The Department may adopt rules to implement this Chapter.
39 (f) Civil Penalties. – The clear proceeds of civil penalties provided for in this section
40 shall be remitted to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2.
41 "§ 114B-3. Age verification for social media platforms.
42 (a) A social media platform must use either anonymous age verification or standard age
43 verification to verify that an account holder is 16 years of age or older and, except as provided in
44 G.S. 114B-2(b), prevent creation of an account by a person younger than 16 years of age. The
45 social media platform must offer anonymous age verification and standard age verification, and
46 a person attempting to create an account may select which method will be used to verify the
47 person's age.
48 (b) A social media platform must ensure that the requirements of subsection (c) of this
49 section are met.
50 (c) A third party conducting anonymous age verification pursuant to this section must
51 comply with all of the following:
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 47

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Shall not retain personal identifying information used to verify age once the
2 age of an account holder or a person seeking an account has been verified.
3 (2) Shall not use personal identifying information used to verify age for any other
4 purpose.
5 (3) Must keep anonymous any personal identifying information used to verify
6 age. The information may not be shared or otherwise communicated to any
7 person.
8 (4) Must protect personal identifying information used to verify age from
9 unauthorized or illegal access, destruction, use, modification, or disclosure
10 through reasonable security procedures and practices appropriate to the nature
11 of the personal information.
12 (d) Any violation of subsection (a) or (b) of this section is deemed an unfair and deceptive
13 trade practice actionable under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes solely by the Department on
14 behalf of a resident minor against a social media platform.
15 If the Department has reason to believe that a social media platform is in violation, the
16 Department may bring an action against the social media platform for an unfair or deceptive act
17 or practice under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes. In addition to other remedies allowed by
18 law, the Department may collect a civil penalty of up to fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) per
19 violation and reasonable attorneys' fees and court costs.
20 When the social media platform's failure to comply with subsection (a) or (b) of this section
21 is a consistent pattern of knowing or reckless conduct, punitive damages may be assessed against
22 the social media platform.
23 "§ 114B-4. Miscellaneous provisions.
24 (a) It is the intent of the General Assembly that this Chapter be liberally construed for the
25 protection of minors.
26 (b) If any provision of this Chapter or its application to any person or circumstances is
27 held invalid, the invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this Chapter which
28 can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end, the provisions of
29 this Chapter are severable."
30 SECTION 5.13.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025.
