32 RESIDENTIAL BUILDING CODE/FAMILY CHILD CARE HOME CLASSIFICATION
33 SECTION 5.14.(a) Definitions. – For the purposes of this section, the following
34 definitions apply:
35 (1) Code. – The North Carolina State Building Code, and amendments to the
36 Code, as adopted by the Councils.
37 (2) Councils. – The Residential Code Council and the Building Code Council.
38 (3) Family child care home. – As described in G.S. 110-86(3)b.
39 SECTION 5.14.(b) Family Child Care Home. – Until the effective date of the rules
40 to create a family child care home occupancy classification within a dwelling subject to the North
41 Carolina Residential Code, the Office of the State Fire Marshal, the Councils, and State and local
42 governments enforcing the Code shall adhere to family child care home requirements as provided
43 in subsection (c) of this section.
44 SECTION 5.14.(c) Implementation. – Notwithstanding Section 310, Residential
45 Group R, of the North Carolina Building Code, and Section 203.10, Residential Group R, of the
46 North Carolina Fire Code, a family child care home located within a dwelling subject to the North
47 Carolina Residential Code shall be treated as a Residential Group R-3 occupancy. The building
48 where the family child care home is located shall be permitted to comply with the North Carolina
49 Residential Code, provided that a family child care home must meet only the following additional
50 requirements:
Page 48 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Rooms and areas within a family child care home where occupants receive
2 care shall be on the same level of exit discharge.
3 (2) Rooms and areas within a family child care home where occupants receive
4 care shall be located on the same level with, and within a maximum of 40 feet
5 travel distance to, at least one 2A:10B:C fire extinguisher.
6 (3) A family child care home shall have and maintain a Fire Safety, Evacuation,
7 and Lockdown Plan compliant with Section 404 of the North Carolina Fire
8 Code.
9 (4) A family child care home shall have carbon monoxide alarm and detection
10 systems compliant with Section R315 of the North Carolina Residential Code.
11 (5) A family child care home shall have smoke alarms compliant with Section
12 R314 of the North Carolina Residential Code.
13 SECTION 5.14.(d) Additional Residential Code Council Rulemaking Authority. –
14 The Residential Code Council shall adopt rules to amend the North Carolina Residential Code to
15 create a family child care home occupancy classification within a dwelling subject to the North
16 Carolina Residential Code consistent with subsection (c) of this section. Notwithstanding
17 G.S. 150B-19(4), the rules adopted by the Residential Code Council pursuant to this subsection
18 shall be substantively identical to the provisions of subsection (c) of this section. Rules adopted
19 pursuant to this subsection are not subject to Part 3 of Article 2A of Chapter 150B of the General
20 Statutes. Rules adopted pursuant to this subsection shall become effective as provided in
21 G.S. 150B-21.3(b1), as though 10 or more written objections had been received as provided in
22 G.S. 150B-21.3(b2).
23 SECTION 5.14.(e) Additional Building Code Council Rulemaking Authority. – The
