15 diplomas, and (iii) meet federal and State reporting requirements related to the test.
16 (t) The purpose of the first semester of the Gateway to College Program is to address
17 additional support to successfully complete the program. Students may need to take
18 developmental courses necessary for the transition to more challenging courses; therefore, the
19 State Board of Community Colleges shall (i) permit high school students who are enrolled in
20 Gateway to College Programs to enroll in developmental courses based on an assessment of their
21 individual student needs by a high school and community college staff team and (ii) include this
22 coursework in computing the budget FTE for the colleges.
23 (u) The State Board of Community Colleges shall direct each community college to adopt
24 a policy that authorizes a minimum of two excused absences each academic year for religious
25 observances required by the faith of a student. The policy may require that the student provide
26 written notice of the request for an excused absence a reasonable time prior to the religious
27 observance. The policy shall also provide that the student shall be given the opportunity to make
28 up any tests or other work missed due to an excused absence for a religious observance.
29 (v) Community colleges may teach curriculum courses at any time during the year,
30 including the summer term. Student membership hours from these courses shall be counted when
31 computing full-time equivalent students (FTE) for use in budget funding formulas at the State
32 level.
33 (w) The State Board of Community Colleges shall review, at least every five years,
34 service areas that include counties assigned to more than one community college to determine
35 the feasibility of continuing to assign those counties to more than one community college. The
36 State Board shall revise service areas as needed to ensure that counties are served effectively.
37 The first review and any revisions shall be completed no later than March 1, 2016, and the State
38 Board shall report its findings and any revisions to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight
39 Committee no later than March 1, 2016. All subsequent reviews and revisions shall also be
40 submitted to the Committee.
41 (x) In addition to the evaluation of cooperative innovative high schools by the State Board
42 of Education pursuant to G.S. 115C-238.55, the State Board of Community Colleges, in
43 conjunction with the State Board of Education and the Board of Governors of The University of
44 North Carolina, shall evaluate the success of students participating in the Career and College
45 Promise Program, including the College Transfer pathway and the Career and Technical
46 Education pathway. Success shall be measured by high school retention rates, high school
47 completion rates, high school dropout rates, certification and associate degree completion,
48 admission to four-year institutions, postgraduation employment in career or study-related fields,
49 and employer satisfaction of employees who participated in the programs. The evaluation shall
50 also include an analysis of the cost of students participating in each of the programs within the
51 Career and College Promise Program, including at least the following:
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 67

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Total enrollment funding, the number of budgeted full-time equivalent
2 students, and the number of students enrolled in courses through cooperative
3 innovative high schools, the College Transfer pathway, and the Career and
4 Technical Education pathway.
5 (2) The cost and number of waivers of tuition and registration fees provided for
6 students enrolled in courses through cooperative innovative high schools, the
7 College Transfer pathway, and the Career and Technical Education pathway.
