General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) To establish and administer standards for professional personnel, curricula,
2 admissions, and graduation.
3 (4) To regulate the awarding of degrees, diplomas, and certificates.
4 (5) To establish and regulate student tuition and fees within policies for tuition
5 and fees established by the General Assembly.
6 (6) To establish and regulate financial accounting procedures.
7 (c) Salaries. – The State Board shall establish standards and scales for salaries and
8 allotments paid from funds administered by the State Board, and all employees of the institutions
9 shall be exempt from the provisions of the North Carolina Human Resources Act. Any and all
10 salary caps set by the State Board for community college presidents shall apply only to the
11 State-paid portion of the salary. Except as otherwise provided by law, the employer contribution
12 rate on the local-paid portion of the salary, to be paid from local funds, shall be set by the State
13 Treasurer based on actuarial recommendations.
14 (d) Faculty Credentials. – The State Board of Community Colleges shall require each
15 community college to meet the faculty credential requirements of its accrediting agency for all
16 community college programs.
17 "§ 115D-6.2. Accreditation.Accreditation policy.
18 The State Board of Community Colleges shall adopt a policy requiring community colleges
19 to be accredited in accordance with G.S. 115D-21.2.
20 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
21 (1) Accreditation cycle. – The period of time during which a community college
22 is accredited.
23 (2) Accrediting agency. – An agency or association that accredits institutions of
24 higher education.
25 (3) Regional accrediting agency. – One of the following accrediting agencies:
26 a. Higher Learning Commission.
27 b. Middle States Commission on Higher Education.
28 c. New England Commission on Higher Education.
29 d. Northwest Commission on Colleges and Universities.
30 e. Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on
31 Colleges.
32 f. Western Association of Schools and Colleges Accrediting
33 Commission for Community and Junior Colleges.
34 (b) Prohibit Consecutive Accreditation by an Accrediting Agency. – A community
35 college shall not receive accreditation by an accrediting agency for consecutive accreditation
36 cycles except as provided in subsection (c) of this section.
37 (c) Accreditation Transfer Procedure. – A community college that pursues accreditation
38 with a different accrediting agency in accordance with this section shall pursue accreditation with
39 a regional accrediting agency. If the community college is not granted candidacy status by any
40 regional accrediting agency that is different from its current accrediting agency at least three
41 years prior to the expiration of its current accreditation, the community college may remain with
42 its current accrediting agency for an additional accreditation cycle.
43 (d) Certain Programs Exempt. – The requirements of this section do not apply to
44 professional, departmental, or certificate programs at community colleges that have specific
45 accreditation requirements or best practices, as identified by the State Board of Community
46 Colleges.
47 (e) Cause of Action. – A community college may bring a civil action, as follows:
48 (1) Against any person who makes a false statement to the accrediting agency of
49 the community college, if all of the following criteria are met:
50 a. The statement, if true, would mean the community college is out of
51 compliance with its accreditation standards.
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 71

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. The person made the statement with knowledge that the statement was
2 false or with reckless disregard as to whether it was false.
3 c. The accrediting agency conducted a review of the community college
4 as a proximate result of the statement.
5 d. The review caused the community college to incur costs.
6 (2) A community college that prevails on a cause of action initiated pursuant to
7 this subsection shall be entitled to the following:
8 a. Costs related to the review conducted by the accrediting agency,
9 including for the following:
10 1. Additional hours worked by community college personnel.
11 2. Contracted services, including outside legal counsel.
12 3. Travel, lodging, and food expenses.
13 4. Fees required by the agency.
14 b. Reasonable attorney fees.
15 c. Court costs.
