14 information technology, electrical line worker, and manufacturing programs and may include
15 other programs to meet local workforce needs.
16 (c) Award Amounts. – To the extent funds are made available for the Program, the State
17 Board of Community Colleges shall award grants in an amount of up to seven hundred fifty
18 dollars ($750.00) to students pursuing short-term, noncredit State and industry workforce
19 credentials. The State Board of Community Colleges shall establish criteria for initial and
20 continuing eligibility for students. At a minimum, students shall be required to qualify as a
21 resident for tuition purposes under the criteria set forth in G.S. 116-143.1 and in accordance with
22 the coordinated and centralized residency determination process administered by the State
23 Education Assistance Authority.
24 (d) Report. – The State Board shall submit a report by April 1 annually on the Program
25 to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division. The
26 report shall contain, for each academic year and by programs of study, the amount of grant funds
27 disbursed and the number of eligible students receiving funds.
28 "§ 115D-10.21. Training programs for students with intellectual and developmental
29 disabilities.
30 (a) The State Board of Community Colleges shall establish a community college training
31 program for up to 15 community colleges. The program shall provide opportunities for
32 micro-credentials or other credentials that lead to increased employment outcomes for
33 individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities (IDD). To the extent funds are
34 appropriated for this purpose, the program shall improve the ability of participating community
35 colleges to offer training and educational components that include improving employability skills
36 and providing on-the-job training and apprenticeships with business and industry for individuals
37 with IDD. The goal of the program shall be to inform community colleges and address
38 cross-departmental supports within the individual community colleges on programs for
39 individuals with IDD related to at least the following:
40 (1) Establishing best practices for providing vocational training for individuals
41 with IDD.
42 (2) Providing financial and benefits counseling.
43 (3) Developing strategies on integrating assistive technology.
44 (4) Maximizing access, with supports, to credential and degree programs,
45 including micro-credentials that are established by the State Board.
46 (5) Identifying methods to increase orientation and integration of individuals with
47 IDD into the college community to the greatest extent possible.
48 (6) Determining a needs assessment, marketing, and evaluation to serve a broad
49 array of individuals with developmental and other similar disabilities or
50 learning challenges to assure adequate demand for new or existing programs.
