5 ELEMENTARY AND MIDDLE SCHOOL LITERACY IMPROVEMENT
6 SECTION 7.13.(a) G.S. 115C-83.6 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 115C-83.6. Facilitating early grade reading proficiency.
8 (a) Kindergarten, first, second, and third Kindergarten through fifth grade students shall
9 be assessed with valid, reliable, formative, and diagnostic reading assessments made available to
10 local school administrative units by the State Board of Education pursuant to
11 G.S. 115C-174.11(a). Difficulty with reading development identified through administration of
12 formative and diagnostic assessments shall be addressed with literacy interventions outlined in
13 the student's Individual Reading Plan. Parents or guardians of first and second grade students
14 offered a reading camp as a literacy intervention shall be encouraged to enroll their student in the
15 reading camp provided by the local school administrative unit. Parents or guardians of a student
16 identified as demonstrating reading comprehension below grade level shall make the final
17 decision regarding a student's reading camp attendance.
18 (a1) Kindergarten through third fifth grade reading assessments shall yield data that can
19 be used with the Education Value-Added Assessment System (EVAAS) to analyze student data
20 to identify root causes for difficulty with reading development and to determine actions to address
21 them.
22 (a2) The Department of Public Instruction shall provide for EVAAS analysis all formative
23 and diagnostic assessment data collected pursuant to this section for kindergarten through third
24 fifth grade. The Department shall use a uniform template for all data collected, and the template
25 shall be used each time data is provided. The template shall include clear designations for each
26 data component reported.
27 (b) Formative and diagnostic assessments and resultant literacy interventions shall
28 address oral language, phonological and phonemic awareness, phonics, vocabulary, fluency, and
29 comprehension using developmentally appropriate practices. These assessments may be
30 administered by computer or other electronic device.
31 (c) Local school administrative units are encouraged to partner with community
32 organizations, businesses, and other groups to provide volunteers, mentors, or tutors to assist
33 with the provision of literacy interventions that enhance reading development and proficiency."
34 SECTION 7.13.(b) G.S. 115C-83.6B(a) reads as rewritten:
35 "(a) An Individual Reading Plan (IRP) shall be developed for any student in kindergarten
36 through third fifth grade demonstrating difficulty with reading development based on the results
37 of either (i) the first diagnostic or formative assessment of the school year or (ii) the first
38 diagnostic or formative assessment of the second semester of the school year. The IRP shall be
39 continually adjusted based on multiple data sources as prescribed by the Department of Public
40 Instruction, indicating that the student is not progressing toward grade-level standards in one or
41 more major reading areas. Based on the most recently collected data, the IRP shall include the
42 following information, specific to the identified student:
43 (1) The specific reading skill deficiencies identified by assessment data.
44 (2) Goals and benchmarks for growth.
45 (3) The means by which progress will be monitored and evaluated.
46 (4) The specific additional literacy interventions the student will receive.
47 (5) The Science of Reading-based instructional programming the teacher will
48 implement.
49 (6) Any additional services the teacher deems appropriate to accelerate the
50 student's reading skill and development."
51 SECTION 7.13.(c) G.S. 115C-83.9(a) reads as rewritten:
