20 CTE MODERNIZATION
21 SECTION 7.38. Of the funds appropriated to the Department of Public Instruction
22 in this act, up to two million dollars ($2,000,000) in nonrecurring funds for each year of the
23 2025-2027 fiscal biennium shall be used to create a grant program for modernization of Career
24 and Technical Education (CTE) programming, materials, training, and professional development
25 for courses conducted in grades six through 12. The Department shall establish a grant program
26 for each school year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium to which a public school unit or regional
27 partnership of more than one public school unit may apply to receive funds if a school within the
28 unit or partnership has an existing CTE program. Grant recipients shall use the funds distributed
29 to them under this section to procure and implement an online digital CTE learning platform
30 containing comprehensive courses with lesson plans, media-rich content and activities, and
31 interactive assessments that align with the North Carolina Career and Technical Education
32 Standards. The platform shall have modules that assist teachers in preparing students for
33 high-wage, high-growth career areas. By October 1, 2025, the Department shall select approved
34 providers to guarantee consistency throughout the State. Any selected digital CTE learning
35 platform shall include at least all of the following components:
36 (1) Instructional strategies and guided lesson plans to assist teachers with
37 classroom implementation and instructional differentiation.
38 (2) Media-based instructional content for providing demonstrations and
39 instruction on skills required for applicable career areas.
40 (3) Multiple methods of delivery of instruction, including at least face-to-face,
41 self-paced, and distance or hybrid learning.
42 (4) Guided projects and activities to incorporate hands-on application of skills.
43 (5) A focus on mastery-based learning.
44 (6) Reporting features to provide data on student progress.
45 (7) Guidance for students to obtain industry-recognized certifications.
46 (8) Career connections to provide examples of career opportunities following
47 graduation from high school.
