38 INTERSTATE COMPACT FOR SCHOOL PSYCHOLOGISTS
39 SECTION 7.48.(a) Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by adding a
40 new Article to read:
41 "Article 17F.
42 "School Psychologist Interstate Licensure Compact.
43 "§ 115C-270.40. Purpose.
44 The purpose of this Compact is to facilitate the interstate practice of School Psychology in
45 educational or school settings, and in so doing to improve the availability of School
46 Psychological Services to the public. This Compact is intended to establish a pathway to allow
47 School Psychologists to obtain equivalent licenses to provide School Psychological Services in
48 any Member State. In this way, this Compact shall enable the Member States to ensure that safe
49 and effective School Psychological Services are available and delivered by appropriately
50 qualified professionals in their educational settings. To facilitate the objectives described above,
51 this Compact does the following:
Page 128 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Enables School Psychologists who qualify for receipt of an Equivalent
2 License to practice in other Member States without first satisfying
3 burdensome and duplicative requirements.
4 (2) Promotes the mobility of School Psychologists between and among the
5 Member States in order to address workforce shortages and to ensure that safe
6 and reliable School Psychological Services are available in each Member
7 State.
8 (3) Enhances the public accessibility of School Psychological Services by
9 increasing the availability of qualified, licensed School Psychologists through
10 the establishment of an efficient and streamlined pathway for Licensees to
11 practice in other Member States.
12 (4) Preserves and respects the authority of each Member State to protect the health
13 and safety of its residents by ensuring that only qualified, licensed
14 professionals are authorized to provide School Psychological Services within
15 that state.
16 (5) Requires School Psychologists practicing within a Member State to comply
17 with the Scope of Practice laws present in the state where the School
18 Psychological Services are being provided.
19 (6) Promotes cooperation between the Member States in regulating the practice
20 of School Psychology within those states.
21 (7) Facilitates the relocation of military members and their spouses who are
22 licensed to provide School Psychological Services.
23 "§ 115C-270.41. Definitions.
24 The following definitions shall apply in this Article:
25 (1) Active Military Member. – Any person with full-time duty status in the Armed
26 Forces of the United States, including members of the National Guard and
27 Reserve.
28 (2) Adverse Action. – Disciplinary action or encumbrance imposed on a License
29 by a State Licensing Authority.
30 (3) Alternative Program. – A nondisciplinary, prosecutorial diversion,
31 monitoring, or practice remediation process entered into in lieu of an Adverse
32 Action which is applicable to a School Psychologist and approved by the State
33 Licensing Authority of a Member State in which the participating School
34 Psychologist is licensed. This includes, but is not limited to, programs to
35 which Licensees with substance abuse or addiction issues may be referred in
36 lieu of an Adverse Action.
37 (4) Commissioner. – The individual appointed by a Member State to serve as the
38 representative to the Commission for that Member State.
39 (5) Compact. – This School Psychologist Interstate Licensure Compact.
40 (6) Continuing Professional Education. – A requirement, imposed by a Member
41 State as a condition of License renewal to provide evidence of successful
42 participation in professional educational activities relevant to the provision of
43 School Psychological Services.
44 (7) Criminal Background Check. – The submission of fingerprints or other
45 biometric information for a License applicant for the purpose of obtaining that
46 applicant's criminal history record information, as defined in 28 C.F.R. §
47 20.3(d), and the state's criminal history record repository, as defined in 28
48 C.F.R. § 20.3(f).
49 (8) Doctoral Level Degree. – A graduate degree program that consists of at least
50 90 graduate semester hours in the field of School Psychology, including a
51 supervised internship.
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 129

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (9) Encumbered License. – A License that a State Licensing Authority has limited
2 in any way other than through an Alternative Program, including temporary
3 or provisional licenses.
4 (10) Executive Committee. – The Commission's Chair, Vice-Chair, Secretary, and
5 Treasurer and any other Commissioners as may be determined by
6 Commission Rule or bylaw.
7 (11) Equivalent License. – A License to practice School Psychology which a
8 Member State has identified as a License which may be provided to School
9 Psychologists from other Member States pursuant to this Compact.
10 (12) Home State. – The Member State that issued the Home State License to the
11 Licensee and is the Licensee's primary state of practice.
12 (13) Home State License. – The License that is not an Encumbered License issued
13 by the Home State to provide School Psychological Services.
14 (14) License. – A current license, certification, or other authorization granted by a
15 Member State's Licensing Authority that permits an individual to provide
16 School Psychological Services.
17 (15) Licensee. – An individual who holds a License from a Member State to
18 provide School Psychological Services.
19 (16) Member State. – A state that has enacted the Compact and been admitted to
20 the Commission in accordance with the provisions herein and Commission
21 Rules.
22 (17) Model Compact. – The model language for the School Psychologist Interstate
23 Licensure Compact on file with the Council of State Governments or other
24 entity as designated by the Commission.
25 (18) Practice of School Psychology. – The delivery of School Psychological
26 Services.
27 (19) Qualifying National Exam. – A national licensing examination endorsed by
28 the National Association of School Psychologists and any other exam as
29 approved by the Rules of the Commission.
30 (20) Qualifying School Psychologist Education Program. – An education program
31 which awards a Specialist-Level or Doctoral-Level degree or equivalent upon
32 completion and is approved by the Rules of the Commission as meeting the
33 necessary minimum educational standards to ensure that its graduates are
34 ready, qualified, and able to engage in the Practice of School Psychology.
35 (21) Remote State. – A Member State other than the Home State where a Licensee
36 holds a License through the Compact.
37 (22) Rule. – A regulation promulgated by an entity, including, but not limited to,
38 the Commission and the State Licensing Authority of each Member State, that
39 has the force of law.
40 (23) School Psychological Services. – Academic, mental, and behavioral health
41 services, including assessment, prevention, consultation and collaboration,
42 intervention, and evaluation provided by a School Psychologist in a school, as
43 outlined in applicable professional standards as determined by Commission
44 Rule.
45 (24) School Psychologist. – An individual who has met the requirements to obtain
46 a Home State License that legally conveys the professional title of School
47 Psychologist, or its equivalent, as determined by the Rules of the Commission.
48 (25) School Psychologist Interstate Licensure Compact Commission
49 (Commission). – The joint government agency established by this Compact
50 whose membership consists of representatives from each Member State that
51 has enacted the Compact, and as further described in G.S. 115C-270.46.
