1 (26) Scope of Practice. – The procedures, actions, and processes a School
2 Psychologist licensed in a state is permitted to undertake in that state and the
3 circumstances under which that Licensee is permitted to undertake those
4 procedures, actions, and processes. Such procedures, actions, and processes,
5 and the circumstances under which they may be undertaken, may be
6 established through means, including, but not limited to, statute, regulations,
7 case law, and other processes available to the State Licensing Authority or
8 other government agency.
9 (27) Specialist-Level Degree. – A degree program that requires at least 60 graduate
10 semester hours or equivalent in the field of School Psychology, including a
11 supervised internship.
12 (28) State. – Any state, commonwealth, district, or territory of the United States of
13 America.
14 (29) State Licensing Authority. – A Member State's regulatory body responsible
15 for issuing Licenses or otherwise overseeing the Practice of School
16 Psychology.
17 (30) State Specific Requirement. – A requirement for licensure covered in
18 coursework or examination that includes content of unique interest to the state.
19 (31) Unencumbered License. – A License that authorizes a Licensee to engage in
20 the full and unrestricted Practice of School Psychology.
21 "§ 115C-270.42. State participation in the Compact.
22 (a) To be eligible to join this Compact, and to maintain eligibility as a Member State, a
23 state must do the following:
24 (1) Enact a Compact statute that is not materially different from the Model
25 Compact as defined in the Commission's Rules.
26 (2) Participate in the sharing of information with other Member States as
27 reasonably necessary to accomplish the objectives of this Compact, and as
28 further defined in G.S. 115C-270.47.
29 (3) Identify and maintain with the Commission a list of Equivalent Licenses
30 available to Licensees who hold a Home State License under this Compact.
31 (4) Have a mechanism in place for receiving and investigating complaints about
32 Licensees.
33 (5) Notify the Commission, in compliance with the terms of the Compact and the
34 Commission's Rules, of any Adverse Action taken against a Licensee, or of
35 the availability of investigative information which relates to a Licensee or
36 applicant for licensure.
37 (6) Require that applicants for a Home State License have done the following:
38 a. Taken and passed a Qualifying National Exam as defined by the Rules
39 of the Commission.
40 b. Completed a minimum of 1200 hours of supervised internship, of
41 which at least 600 must have been completed in a School, prior to
42 being approved for licensure.
43 c. Graduated from a Qualifying School Psychologist Education Program.
44 (7) Comply with the terms of this Compact and the Rules of the Commission.
45 (b) Each Member State shall grant an Equivalent License to practice School Psychology
46 in that state upon application by a Licensee who satisfies the criteria of G.S. 115C-270.43(a).
47 Each Member State shall grant renewal of the Equivalent License to a Licensee who satisfies the
48 criteria of G.S. 115C-270.43(b).
49 (c) Member States may set and collect a fee for granting an Equivalent License.
