43 CLASS SIZE EXEMPTIONS FOR GROWING COUNTIES
44 SECTION 7.50.(a) G.S. 115C-301 reads as rewritten:
45 "§ 115C-301. Allocation of teachers; class size.
46 …
47 (c) Maximum Class Size for Kindergarten Through Third Grade. – The average class size
48 for kindergarten through third grade in a local school administrative unit shall be as follows:
49 (1) Growing local school administrative units. – If a local school administrative
50 unit has an increase in student population of one-half percent (0.5%) of the
51 average daily membership of the local school administrative unit for two
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 141

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 consecutive years, then the unit shall be considered a growing local school
2 administrative unit for the two years immediately following the second year
3 of student population increase. Growing local school administrative units may
4 exceed the allotment ratios listed in subdivision (2) of this subsection by up to
5 three students.
6 (2) All other local school administrative units. – For any local school
7 administrative unit not qualifying as growing under subdivision (1) of this
8 subsection, the average class size for kindergarten through third grade in the
9 local school administrative unit shall at no time exceed the funded allotment
10 ratio of teachers to students in kindergarten through third grade. At the end of
11 the second school month and for the remainder of the school year, the size of
12 an individual class in kindergarten through third grade shall not exceed the
13 allotment ratio by more than three students. The funded class size allotment
14 ratio for kindergarten through third grade shall be as follows:
15 (1)a. For kindergarten, one teacher per 18 students.
16 (2)b. For first grade, one teacher per 16 students.
17 (3)c. For second grade, one teacher per 17 students.
18 (4)d. For third grade, one teacher per 17 students.
19 In grades four through 12, local school administrative units shall have the maximum
20 flexibility to use allotted teacher positions to maximize student achievement.
21 …
22 (g) Waivers and Allotment Adjustments. – Local boards of education shall report
23 exceptions to the class size requirements set out for kindergarten through third grade and
24 significant increases in class size at other grade levels to the State Board and shall request
25 allotment adjustments at any grade level, waivers from the requirements for kindergarten through
26 third grade, or both. Within 45 days of receipt of reports, the State Board of Education, within
27 funds available, may allot additional positions at any grade level. The State Board shall not grant
28 waivers for excess class size in kindergarten through third grade, except under the following
29 circumstances:
30 (1) Emergencies or acts of God that impact the availability of classroom space or
31 facilities.
32 (2) An unanticipated increase in student population of an individual school in
33 excess of two percent (2%) of the average daily membership of that school.
34 The State Board of Education shall allow waivers in consecutive years for
35 schools located in growing local school administrative units that continue to
36 qualify for a waiver under this subdivision.
37 (3) Organizational problems in geographically isolated local school
38 administrative units in which the average daily membership is less than one
39 and one-half per square mile.
40 (4) Classes organized for a solitary curricular area.
41 (5) A charter school closure.
42 (6) The performance grade of the school under G.S. 115C-12(9)c1 and
43 G.S. 115C-83.15 is a B or better and the school is located in a growing local
44 school administrative unit. Waivers granted pursuant to this subsection shall
45 be for an additional five students per class.
46 The State Board shall report on all waivers to the Joint Legislative Commission on
47 Governmental Operations within 30 days of the grant of the waiver. The report shall include the
48 local school administrative unit, school, and class or classes for which the waiver was granted,
49 the statutory grounds for the waiver, and the terms of the waiver. A waiver for excess class size
50 in kindergarten through third grade shall not become effective until the State Board submits the
51 report to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations.
