18 AFTER SCHOOL ROBOTICS GRANT PROGRAM
19 SECTION 7.51.(a) Program; Purpose. – To the extent funds are made available for
20 the purpose, there is established the Educational and Competitive After-School Robotics Grant
21 Program (Program) for each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium. The purpose of the Program
22 shall be to (i) promote evidence-based, after-school programs for robotics education and
23 competition and (ii) motivate students to pursue education and career opportunities in science,
24 technology, engineering, and mathematics while building critical life and work-related skills.
25 SECTION 7.51.(b) Eligibility. – Any public school unit is eligible to apply to the
26 Department of Public Instruction for a grant to develop an educational and competitive
27 after-school robotics program with a robotics partner in any high school within the public school
28 unit. As used in this subsection, the term "robotics partner" shall refer to a third-party entity, such
29 as a nonprofit organization or institution of higher education, approved by the Department of
30 Public Instruction that is able to provide adequate support for an after-school robotics program.
31 In order to provide adequate support, a robotics partner must meet at least all of the following
32 criteria:
33 (1) Have a national presence in robotics education and competition.
34 (2) Provide adequate instruction and programming for students and adult
35 volunteers in (i) robotics education, (ii) project-based learning, and (iii)
36 competitive robotics.
37 (3) Promote a safe and equitable social environment.
38 SECTION 7.51.(c) Applications; Criteria and Guidelines. – No later than August 1
39 of each year that funds are made available for the Program, the Department shall develop and
40 publish criteria and guidelines for the application process for the Program in the upcoming school
41 year, including any documentation required to be submitted by the applicants. The Department
42 shall accept applications until September 30 of each school year. Applications shall include, at a
43 minimum, the following information:
44 (1) Evidence that the applicant has or will be able to establish a relationship with
45 a robotics partner.
46 (2) A proposed budget for the educational and competitive after-school robotics
47 program.
48 SECTION 7.51.(d) Award and Use of Funds. – The Department shall prioritize
49 awarding grants to public school units that participated in the Program in the prior school year.
50 Grant awards shall not exceed fifteen thousand dollars ($15,000) per participating high school in
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 143

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the public school unit. The Department shall award grants to the selected applicants by October
2 31 of each year of the Program. Funds may be used for any of the following purposes:
3 (1) Establishing a relationship with a robotics partner.
4 (2) Purchasing robotics kits.
5 (3) Providing stipends for coaches.
6 (4) Making payments associated with participation in a robotics league or robotics
7 competition.
8 (5) Paying fees incurred as part of the administration of a robotics team.
9 SECTION 7.51.(e) Reporting. – No later than October 15 of each year in which
10 funds are made available for the Program, the Department shall report the following information
11 from the prior school year to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee and the Fiscal
12 Research Division:
13 (1) Number and amounts of grants awarded.
14 (2) Identities of the public school units receiving grants.
15 (3) Identities of public school units that applied for grants but did not receive one.
16 (4) The extent to which students participating in after-school robotics programs
17 funded by the Program experienced measurable improvement in academic
18 performance, if any.
