32 RESPONSIBLE FATHERHOOD NORTH CAROLINA ACT
33 SECTION 7.53.(a) The General Assembly recognizes that families are stronger
34 when both parents act responsibly in caring for their children. It is the intent of the General
35 Assembly to recognize and support the important and unique role that fathers play in ensuring
36 the physical, emotional, and economic well-being of their children and families.
37 SECTION 7.53.(b) The Department shall contract for the development and
38 implementation of the Responsible Fatherhood North Carolina program. The program shall
39 provide an opportunity for every father in the State to be able to obtain information and
40 inspiration that will motivate and enable him to enhance his abilities as a father, recognizing that
41 some fathers have greater challenges than others and would benefit from greater support. The
42 entity the Department contracts with to develop, implement, and manage the program, "Program
43 Manager," shall be a nonprofit organization that satisfies all of the following criteria:
44 (1) Has a history of focusing on responsible fatherhood, including providing
45 online resources to fathers, and engaging fathers, father figures, and children
46 through community-based and school-based events to encourage responsible
47 fatherhood.
48 (2) Has the organizational capacity to manage a statewide initiative and
49 successfully carry out the requirements of this section.
50 SECTION 7.53.(c) The Program Manager shall be solely responsible for developing,
51 implementing, and managing the program which shall include at least the following:
Page 144 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) A statewide media campaign that increases the awareness and importance of
2 fathers being involved in their children's lives.
3 (2) Resources and information for fathers and father figures to increase
4 engagement and involvement in their children's lives.
5 (3) Promotion of related fatherhood programs that are provided by the
6 Department of Public Instruction, the Community College System, or The
7 University of North Carolina System.
8 SECTION 7.53.(d) To most effectively use the funds appropriated to this program,
9 the Program Manager shall identify and use other existing media assets, content, and online
10 resources it deems appropriate, including any existing media assets, content, and online resources
11 it has available, to implement and execute the items required by this section.
12 SECTION 7.53.(e) The Program Manager shall administer a grant program to award
13 grants to nonprofit community-based organizations that address the needs of fathers in
14 accordance with the following:
15 (1) The Program Manager shall award the following types of grants:
16 a. Grants that comprehensively address the needs of fathers, such as
17 assisting them in finding employment, managing child support
18 obligations, transitioning from a period of incarceration, accessing
19 health care, understanding child development, and enhancing
20 parenting skills. Services provided shall be tailored to the needs of the
21 father being served. Case management services shall be provided to
22 the fathers who are served by the grants under this subdivision.
23 b. Grants that provide evidence-based parenting education specifically
24 for fathers. The grants under this subdivision do not require case
25 management services.
26 (2) The Program Manager shall prioritize awarding grants according to the
27 following:
28 a. Need in a geographic area and the population to be served by the grant
29 as indicated by, at a minimum, all of the following:
30 1. Unemployment rates.
31 2. Incarceration rates.
32 3. Housing instability.
33 4. The number of single-parent households.
34 5. The number of public benefit recipients.
35 6. Graduation rates.
36 7. Levels of academic achievement.
37 b. If an applicant has a primary mission of, or a history of a significant
38 focus on and effective work toward, addressing the needs of men in
39 their role as fathers.
40 c. Applicant current and historical involvement in the community being
41 served.
42 d. Applicant commitment and capability to employ competent staff who
43 can effectively engage with the fathers being served, including, at a
44 minimum, those individuals who share a similar background as the
45 fathers being served.
46 e. The number of individuals the applicant plans to serve through the
47 grant and the projected costs for the program.
48 f. Applicant organizational capacity to effectively meet the requirements
49 of the grant and to deliver the programs proposed by the applicant. The
50 Program Manager may offer technical assistance to applicants and
51 grant recipients that have lower organizational capacity as long as such
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 145

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 organizations have, or the organization's leadership has, significant
2 experience serving fathers.
3 (3) Grant recipients shall submit reports to the Department in a format and at
4 intervals prescribed by the Department.
5 SECTION 7.53.(f) Of the funds appropriated to the Department of Public Instruction
6 in this act for the Responsible Fatherhood North Carolina program, the Department shall use up
