34 "§ 115C-229.40. Student admissions and assignment.
35 (a) The regional school may serve grades seven through 12.
36 (b) A student domiciled in a county within the regional school service area is eligible to
37 attend the regional school. A student's eligibility to remain enrolled in the regional school shall
38 terminate at the end of any school year during which a student ceases to satisfy the residency
39 requirements.
40 (c) The board of directors shall establish criteria, standards, and procedures for admission
41 of students. The admission criteria may give priority to students with no parent that has completed
42 a two- or four-year degree and shall include the following:
43 (1) Demonstrated academic achievement.
44 (2) Demonstrated student interest in attendance.
45 (3) Documented parental support for student attendance.
46 (d) If the number of eligible students meeting the board of directors' admission criteria
47 exceeds the seats available, students shall be accepted by lot.
48 "§ 115C-229.45. Employees.
49 The board of directors shall appoint all certified and noncertified staff.
50 (1) The board of directors shall employ and contract with a principal for a term
51 not to exceed three years. The principal shall meet the requirements for
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 151

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 certification set out in G.S. 115C-284, unless waived by the State Board of
2 Education upon submission of a request by the board of directors. The
3 principal shall be responsible for school operations and shall exercise those
4 duties and powers delegated by the board of directors.
5 (2) The board of directors shall employ and contract with necessary teachers to
6 perform the particular service for which they are employed in the school. At
7 least fifty percent (50%) of teachers employed by the board of directors shall
8 hold teacher licensure, unless waived by the State Board of Education upon
9 submission of a request by the board of directors.
10 (3) If a teacher employed by a local school administrative unit makes a written
11 request for a leave of absence to teach at the regional school, the local school
12 administrative unit shall grant the leave for one year. For the initial year of the
13 regional school's operation, the local school administrative unit may require
14 that the request for a leave of absence be made up to 45 days before the teacher
15 would otherwise have to report for duty. After the initial year of the regional
16 school's operation, the local school administrative unit may require that the
17 request for a leave of absence be made up to 90 days before the teacher would
18 otherwise have to report for duty. A local board of education is not required
19 to grant a request for a leave of absence or a request to extend or renew a leave
20 of absence for a teacher who previously has received a leave of absence from
21 that school board under this subdivision. A teacher who has received a leave
22 of absence to teach at a regional school may return to a public school in the
23 local school administrative unit at the end of the leave of absence or upon the
24 end of employment at the regional school if an appropriate position is
25 available. If a teacher has career status under G.S. 115C-325 prior to receiving
26 a leave of absence to teach at the regional school, the teacher may return to a
27 public school in the local school administrative unit with career status at the
28 end of the leave of absence or upon the end of employment at the regional
29 school if an appropriate position is available. If an appropriate position is
30 unavailable, the teacher's name shall be placed on a list of available teachers
31 in accordance with G.S. 115C-325(e)(2).
32 (4) The board of directors also may employ necessary employees who are not
33 required to hold teacher licensure to perform duties other than teaching and
34 may contract for other services.
35 (5) An employee of the board of directors is not an employee of the local school
36 administrative unit in which the regional school is located. The board of
37 directors may discharge certified and noncertified employees according to the
38 terms of the employment contract.
39 (6) Employees of the board of directors shall participate in the Teachers' and State
40 Employees' Retirement System and the State Health Plan on the same terms
41 as employees employed by local boards of education.
42 (7) Employees of the board of directors shall be exempt from Chapter 126 of the
43 General Statutes, except for Articles 6 and 7 and G.S. 126-8.6.
44 (8) Teachers employed by the board of directors shall be eligible for paid parental
45 leave as provided in G.S. 126-8.6. The board of directors shall be eligible to
46 receive funds as provided in G.S. 115C-336.1(b).
47 "§ 115C-229.50. Criminal history record checks.
48 (a) As used in this section:
49 (1) "Criminal history" means a county, state, or federal criminal history of
50 conviction of a crime, whether a misdemeanor or a felony, that indicates an
51 individual (i) poses a threat to the physical safety of students or personnel or
Page 152 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (ii) has demonstrated that he or she does not have the integrity or honesty to
2 fulfill his or her duties as school personnel. These crimes include the following
3 North Carolina crimes contained in any of the following Articles of Chapter
4 14 of the General Statutes: Article 5A, Endangering Executive and
5 Legislative, and Court Officers; Article 6, Homicide; Article 7B, Rape and
6 Other Sex Offenses; Article 8, Assaults; Article 10, Kidnapping and
7 Abduction; Article 13, Malicious Injury or Damage by Use of Explosive or
8 Incendiary Device or Material; Article 14, Burglary and Other
9 Housebreakings; Article 15, Arson and Other Burnings; Article 16, Larceny;
10 Article 17, Robbery; Article 18, Embezzlement; Article 19, False Pretense and
11 Cheats; Article 19A, Obtaining Property or Services by False or Fraudulent
12 Use of Credit Device or Other Means; Article 20, Frauds; Article 21, Forgery;
13 Article 26, Offenses Against Public Morality and Decency; Article 26A, Adult
14 Establishments; Article 27, Prostitution; Article 28, Perjury; Article 29,
15 Bribery; Article 31, Misconduct in Public Office; Article 35, Offenses Against
16 the Public Peace; Article 36A, Riots, Civil Disorders, and Emergencies;
17 Article 39, Protection of Minors; and Article 60, Computer-Related Crime.
18 These crimes also include possession or sale of drugs in violation of the North
19 Carolina Controlled Substances Act, Article 5 of Chapter 90 of the General
20 Statutes, and alcohol-related offenses such as sale to underage persons in
21 violation of G.S. 18B-302 or driving while impaired in violation of
22 G.S. 20-138.1 through G.S. 20-138.5. In addition to the North Carolina crimes
23 listed in this subdivision, such crimes also include similar crimes under federal
24 law or under the laws of other states.
25 (2) "School personnel" means any of the following:
26 a. Member of the board of directors.
27 b. Employee of the regional school.
28 c. Independent contractor or employee of an independent contractor of
29 the regional school if the independent contractor carries out duties
30 customarily performed by school personnel, whether paid with federal,
31 State, local, or other funds, who has significant access to students or
32 who has responsibility for the fiscal management of the regional
33 school.
34 (b) The board of directors shall adopt a policy on whether and under what circumstances
35 school personnel shall be required to be checked for a criminal history. The board of directors
36 shall apply its policy uniformly in requiring school personnel to be checked for a criminal history.
37 The board of directors may grant conditional approval of an application while the board of
38 directors is checking a person's criminal history and making a decision based on the results of
39 the check. The board of directors shall not require school personnel to pay for the criminal history
40 record check authorized under this section.
41 (c) The board of directors shall require the person to be checked by the Department of
42 Public Safety (i) to be fingerprinted and to provide any additional information required by the
43 Department of Public Safety to a person designated by the board of directors or to the local sheriff
44 or the municipal police, whichever is more convenient for the person, and (ii) to sign a form
45 consenting to the check of the criminal record and to the use of fingerprints and other identifying
46 information required by the repositories. The board of directors shall consider refusal to consent
47 when making employment decisions and decisions with regard to independent contractors. The
48 fingerprints of the individual shall be forwarded to the State Bureau of Investigation for a search
49 of the State criminal history record file, and the State Bureau of Investigation shall forward a set
50 of fingerprints to the Federal Bureau of Investigation for a national criminal history record check.
51 The Department of Public Safety shall provide to the board of directors the criminal history from
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 153

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the State and National Repositories of Criminal Histories of any school personnel for which the
2 board of directors requires a criminal history record check. The board of directors shall not
3 require school personnel to pay for the fingerprints authorized under this section.
4 (d) The board of directors shall review the criminal history it receives on an individual.
5 The board of directors shall determine whether the results of the review indicate that the
6 individual (i) poses a threat to the physical safety of students or personnel or (ii) has demonstrated
7 that he or she does not have the integrity or honesty to fulfill his or her duties as school personnel
8 and shall use the information when making employment decisions and decisions with regard to
9 independent contractors. The board of directors shall make written findings with regard to how
10 it used the information when making employment decisions and decisions with regard to
11 independent contractors. The board of directors may delegate any of the duties in this subsection
12 to the principal.
13 (e) The board of directors, or the principal if designated by the board of directors, shall
14 provide to the State Board of Education the criminal history it receives on a person who is
15 certificated, certified, or licensed by the State Board of Education. The State Board of Education
16 shall review the criminal history and determine whether the person's certificate or license should
17 be revoked in accordance with State laws and rules regarding revocation.
18 (f) All the information received by the board of directors through the checking of the
19 criminal history or by the State Board of Education in accordance with this section is privileged
20 information and is not a public record but is for the exclusive use of the board of directors or the
21 State Board of Education. The board of directors or the State Board of Education may destroy
22 the information after it is used for the purposes authorized by this section after one calendar year.
23 (g) There shall be no liability for negligence on the part of the board of directors, or its
24 employees, or the State Board of Education, the Superintendent of Public Instruction, or any of
25 their members or employees, individually or collectively, arising from any act taken or omission
26 by any of them in carrying out the provisions of this section. The immunity established by this
27 subsection shall not extend to gross negligence, wanton conduct, or intentional wrongdoing that
28 would otherwise be actionable. The immunity established by this subsection shall be deemed to
29 have been waived to the extent of indemnification by insurance, indemnification under Articles
30 31A and 31B of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes, and to the extent sovereign immunity is
31 waived under the Tort Claims Act, as set forth in Article 31 of Chapter 143 of the General
32 Statutes.
33 (h) Any applicant for employment who willfully furnishes, supplies, or otherwise gives
34 false information on an employment application that is the basis for a criminal history record
35 check under this section shall be guilty of a Class A1 misdemeanor.
36 (i) The board of directors may adopt a policy providing for uniform periodic checks of
37 criminal history of employees. Boards of directors shall not require employees to pay for the
38 criminal history check authorized under this subsection. A board of directors shall indicate, upon
39 inquiry by any other local board of education, charter school, or regional school in the State as
40 to the reason for an employee's resignation or dismissal. If a teacher's criminal history is relevant
41 to a teacher's resignation, the board of directors shall report to the State Board of Education the
42 reason for an employee's resignation.
43 "§ 115C-229.55. Finance and budget.
44 (a) The board of directors shall have all the rights, duties, and obligations for receipt,
45 accounting, and dispersing of funds for the school, including all the rights, duties, and obligations
46 specified in Article 31 of this Chapter. The board may contract with a local school administrative
47 unit to serve as the finance agent for the board and shall provide reasonable compensation to the
48 local school administrative unit for this service. Upon such agreement, that local school
49 administrative unit shall act as agent for the board in all receipt, accounting, and dispersing
50 functions, but the board shall retain liability for compliance with Article 31 of this Chapter.
