5 (d) CTE Bonuses. – For qualifying career and technical education teachers, bonuses shall
6 be provided in the following amounts:
7 (1) A bonus in the amount of twenty-five dollars ($25.00) for each student taught
8 by a teacher who provided instruction in a course that led to the attainment of
9 an industry certification or credential with a twenty-five dollar ($25.00) value
10 ranking as determined under subsection (e) of this section.
11 (2) A bonus in the amount of fifty dollars ($50.00) for each student taught by a
12 teacher who provided instruction in a course that led to the attainment of an
13 industry certification or credential with a fifty dollar ($50.00) value ranking
14 as determined under subsection (e) of this section.
15 (e) CTE Course Value Ranking. – The Department of Commerce, in consultation with
16 the State Board, shall assign a value ranking for each industry certification and credential based
17 on academic rigor and employment value in accordance with this subsection. Fifty percent (50%)
18 of the ranking shall be based on academic rigor and the remaining fifty percent (50%) on
19 employment value. Academic rigor and employment value shall be based on the following
20 elements:
21 (1) Academic rigor shall be based on the number of instructional hours, including
22 work experience or internship hours, required to earn the industry certification
23 or credential, with extra weight given for coursework that also provides
24 community college credit.
25 (2) Employment value shall be based on the entry wage, growth rate in
26 employment for each occupational category, and average annual openings for
27 the primary occupation linked with the industry certification or credential.
28 (f) Statewide Growth Bonuses. – The Department shall provide bonuses to qualifying
