28 SUPPLEMENTAL FUNDS FOR TEACHER COMPENSATION
29 SECTION 7A.3.(a) Use of Funds. – For each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium,
30 except as provided in subsection (g) of this section, the State Board of Education shall allocate
31 funds pursuant to this section to eligible local school administrative units to provide salary
32 supplements to teachers and qualifying school administrators in those units. Allocation of salary
33 supplements among teachers and qualifying school administrators within each eligible local
34 school administrative unit, including whether a teacher or qualifying school administrator
35 receives a salary supplement and the amount of the supplement provided to that person, shall be
36 determined in the discretion of the local board of education of the eligible unit, except that no
37 individual salary supplement shall exceed the per teacher funding amount awarded to that unit
38 pursuant to subdivision (4) of subsection (c) of this section.
39 SECTION 7A.3.(b) Definitions. – As used in this section, the following definitions
40 shall apply:
41 (1) Adjusted market value of taxable real property. – A county's assessed taxable
42 real property value, using the latest available data published by the
43 Department of Revenue, divided by the county's sales assessment ratio
44 determined under G.S. 105-289(h).
45 (2) Composite value. – For each eligible county, the sum of the following:
46 a. The taxable real property factor multiplied by sixty-five percent
47 (65%).
48 b. The median household income factor multiplied by twenty-five
49 percent (25%).
50 c. The effective tax rate factor multiplied by ten percent (10%).
Page 174 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) County allocation factor. – For each eligible county, the supplement factor for
2 that county divided by the sum of all supplement factors for the State.
3 (4) Effective tax rate. – The actual county tax rate multiplied by the most recent
4 annual sales assessment ratio for that county.
5 (5) Effective tax rate factor. – For each eligible county, the effective tax rate for
6 that county divided by the median effective tax rate in the State.
7 (6) Eligible county. – A county that has an adjusted market value of taxable real
8 property of less than sixty-three billion dollars ($63,000,000,000).
9 (7) Eligible local school administrative unit. – A local school administrative unit
10 located in whole or in part in an eligible county.
11 (8) Eligible school. – A public school that is located in an eligible county and
12 governed by a local school administrative unit.
13 (9) Maintenance of effort amount. – For each local school administrative unit in
14 each fiscal year, the supplant factor multiplied by the total State and non-State
15 funds expended for salaries for teachers from the fiscal year for which the
16 most recent salary data are available.
17 (10) Median household income. – A county's median household income for the
18 most recent 12 months for which data are available, as that term is used in
19 G.S. 143B-437.08.
20 (11) Median household income factor. – For each eligible county, the median
21 household income in the State divided by the median household income for
22 that county.
23 (12) Non-State funds. – Any funds held by a local school administrative unit, other
24 than nonrecurring federal funds received as a result of legislation enacted by
25 Congress in response to COVID-19, that are not State funds.
26 (13) Qualifying school administrator. – Any of the following:
27 a. Assistant principals paid pursuant to G.S. 115C-285(a)(8).
28 b. Principals paid pursuant to G.S. 115C-285(a)(8a).
29 (14) Supplant factor. – For each local school administrative unit in each fiscal year
30 of the fiscal biennium, the total non-State funds expended for salary
31 supplements for teachers in the 2020-2021 fiscal year divided by the total
32 State and non-State funds expended for salaries for teachers in the 2020-2021
33 fiscal year.
34 (15) Supplement factor. – For each eligible county, the composite value multiplied
35 by the number of State-funded teachers employed in a school in the county
36 that is governed by a local school administrative unit.
37 (16) Taxable real property factor. – For each eligible county, the median adjusted
38 market value of taxable real property in the State divided by the adjusted
39 market value of taxable real property for that county.
40 (17) Teacher. – Teachers and instructional support personnel.
41 SECTION 7A.3.(c) Allocation of Funds. – The State Board of Education shall
42 allocate funds for salary supplements to eligible local school administrative units according to
43 the following procedure:
44 (1) County allocation. – For each eligible county, the State Board shall determine
45 a county allocation by multiplying the county allocation factor for that county
46 by the funding amount appropriated pursuant to this section for the applicable
47 fiscal year.
48 (2) Per teacher funding amount. – For each eligible county, the State Board shall
49 determine a per teacher funding amount by dividing the county allocation
50 amounts determined pursuant to subdivision (1) of this subsection by the total
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 175

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 number of State-funded teachers employed in all eligible schools in that
2 county.
3 (3) Unit funding amount. – For each eligible local school administrative unit, the
4 State Board shall determine the funding amount for that unit based on the per
5 teacher funding amount or amounts for the eligible county or counties where
6 the unit is located. For each county with an eligible school governed by the
7 unit, the State Board shall multiply the applicable per teacher funding amount
8 for that county determined pursuant to subdivision (2) of this subsection by
9 the number of State-funded teachers employed in the eligible school in that
10 county. If the unit is located in multiple eligible counties, the State Board shall
11 aggregate those amounts.
12 (4) Allocation and funding cap. – The State Board shall allocate the amount
13 determined pursuant to subdivision (3) of this subsection to each eligible local
14 school administrative unit for each applicable fiscal year, up to a maximum of
15 five thousand dollars ($5,000) per State-funded teacher.
16 SECTION 7A.3.(d) Charter Schools. – Funds appropriated to the Department of
17 Public Instruction pursuant to this section shall be subject to the allocation of funds for charter
18 schools described in G.S. 115C-218.105. The General Assembly encourages charter schools
19 receiving funds pursuant to this section to provide salary supplements to teachers and qualifying
20 school administrators in the charter school in accordance with the requirements of this section.
21 SECTION 7A.3.(e) Formula for Distribution of Supplemental Funding Pursuant to
22 this Section Only. – The formula in this section is solely a basis for distribution of supplemental
23 funding to eligible local school administrative units and is not intended to reflect any measure of
24 the adequacy of the educational program or funding for public schools. The formula is also not
25 intended to reflect any commitment by the General Assembly to appropriate any additional
26 supplemental funds for eligible local school administrative units.
27 SECTION 7A.3.(f) Nonsupplant Requirement. – A local school administrative unit
28 that receives funds under this section shall use those funds to supplement non-State funds
29 provided for salary supplements for teachers and qualifying school administrators and shall not
30 use any State funds, including funds received under this section, Section 7A.4 of S.L. 2023-134,
31 or Section 7A.12 of S.L. 2021-180, to supplant non-State funds provided for salary supplements
32 for teachers and qualifying school administrators. For purposes of this section, a local school
33 administrative unit has supplanted non-State funds if the State Board finds that the amount of
34 non-State funds expended by the unit for salary supplements was less than ninety-five percent
35 (95%) of the maintenance of effort amount for the local school administrative unit.
36 SECTION 7A.3.(g) Nonsupplant Enforcement. – The State Board of Education shall
37 not allocate any funds under this section to a local school administrative unit if it determines that
38 the unit has supplanted non-State funds in violation of subsection (f) of this section.
39 SECTION 7A.3.(h) Reports. – No later than April 15 of each year of the 2025-2027
