32 SECTION 8A.6.(d) Article 23 of Chapter 116 of the General Statutes is amended
33 by adding the following new Part to read:
34 "Part 8. Children of Wartime Veterans Scholarship.
35 "§ 116-209.110. Purpose.
36 In appreciation for the service and sacrifices of North Carolina's war veterans and as evidence
37 of this State's concern for their children, there is established the Children of Wartime Veterans
38 Scholarship Program to be administered by the State Education Assistance Authority. The
39 General Assembly finds that the establishment of the Program is necessary to provide financial
40 assistance from the State to address the unique needs and challenges of the children of wartime
41 veterans to ensure they have opportunities to reach their higher education attainment goals.
42 "§ 116-209.112. Definitions.
43 The following definitions shall apply in this Part:
44 (1) Active federal service. – One of the following:
45 a. Full-time duty in the Armed Forces other than active duty for training.
46 b. Active duty for training, if disability or death occurs (i) as a direct
47 result of armed conflict or (ii) while engaged in extra-hazardous
48 service, including such service under conditions simulating war.
49 (2) Armed Forces. – The United States Army, Navy, Marine Corps, Air Force,
50 Space Force, and Coast Guard, including their reserve components.
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 203

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Authority. – The State Education Assistance Authority established pursuant
2 to this Article.
3 (4) Disability. – A disability of a veteran that qualifies the veteran to receive
4 compensation under 38 U.S.C. § 101.
5 (5) Eligible child. – A person who meets all of the following criteria:
6 a. Is under 25 years of age at the time of application for a scholarship.
7 b. Qualifies as a resident for tuition purposes under the criteria set forth
8 in G.S. 116-143.1 and in accordance with the coordinated and
9 centralized residency determination process administered by the
10 Authority.
11 c. Holds a high school diploma or its equivalent.
12 d. Is the child of a veteran who meets one of the following criteria:
13 1. Is a resident of North Carolina at the time of completion of the
14 application documentation for the Program.
15 2. Was a resident of North Carolina at the time of entrance into
16 service in the Armed Forces.
17 3. Was permanently stationed in North Carolina at the time of his
18 or her death.
19 4. Is an active duty service member permanently stationed in
20 North Carolina at the time of completion of the application
21 documentation for the Program.
22 e. Submits a completed Free Application for Federal Student Aid
23 (FAFSA) to the Authority.
24 (6) Eligible institution. – A State educational institution or a private educational
25 institution.
26 (7) Period of war or wartime. – Any of the periods or circumstances described
27 below:
28 a. Any period of war as defined in 38 U.S.C. § 101.
29 b. Any period of service in the Armed Forces during which the veteran
30 parent of an applicant for a scholarship under this Part suffered death
31 or disability (i) as a direct result of armed conflict or (ii) while engaged
32 in extra-hazardous service, including such service under conditions
33 simulating war.
34 (8) Private educational institution. – An eligible private postsecondary institution
35 as defined in G.S. 116-280(3).
36 (9) Program. – The Children of Wartime Veterans Scholarship Program
37 established by this Part.
38 (10) State educational institution. – Any constituent institution of The University
39 of North Carolina, or any community college operated under the provisions of
40 Chapter 115D of the General Statutes of North Carolina.
41 (11) Veteran. – Either of the following:
42 a. A person who served as a member of the Armed Forces in active
43 federal service during a period of war and who was either separated
44 from the Armed Forces under honorable conditions or who is currently
45 serving in a second or subsequent enlistment.
46 b. A person who was separated from the Armed Forces under honorable
47 conditions and whose death or disability was incurred (i) as a direct
48 result of armed conflict or (ii) while engaged in extra-hazardous
49 service, including such service under conditions simulating war.
50 "§ 116-209.114. Scholarship.
Page 204 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) Scholarship Benefits. – To the extent funds are made available for this purpose,
2 scholarship granted pursuant to this Part shall consist of the following benefits and other
3 requirements and limitations for eligible children enrolled as undergraduate students at eligible
4 institutions:
5 (1) Scholarship funds may be used for any of the following purposes:
6 a. The cost of attendance at an eligible institution, including tuition, fees,
7 room, and board.
8 b. The cost of short-term workforce training courses leading to industry
9 credentials.
10 (2) An eligible child may only receive scholarship funds for a total of four
11 academic years. The eligible child is not required to be continuously enrolled
12 to receive subsequent awards in a term, quarter, or semester. However, the
13 eligible child shall not receive an award after the end of a six-year period
14 beginning on the date a scholarship is first awarded. Whenever an eligible
15 child is enrolled in an eligible institution and the period for a scholarship ends
16 while enrolled in a term, quarter, or semester, such period shall be extended
17 to the end of such term, quarter, or semester, but not beyond the eligibility
18 limitation of four academic years.
19 (3) No scholarship awarded to an eligible child pursuant to this Part shall exceed
20 an amount equal to the highest cost of attendance for attendance at a State
21 educational institution for that academic year.
22 (4) As necessary, the Authority shall reduce a scholarship provided pursuant to
23 this Part so that the sum of all grants and scholarship aid covering the cost of
24 attendance received by the student, including the scholarship under this
25 section, shall not exceed the cost of attendance for the eligible institution at
26 which the student is enrolled.
27 (5) A student who has been awarded a scholarship under this section shall
28 maintain satisfactory academic progress according to the standards of the
29 eligible institution throughout the four academic years for which the student
30 is eligible for a scholarship under this section.
31 (b) Selection of Recipients. – The Authority shall select recipients for scholarships and
32 disburse the scholarships in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 116-209.116. The Authority
33 may contract with another State agency or a third-party entity to determine eligibility and select
34 recipients as required by G.S. 116-209.116(a)(1). In the event there are not sufficient funds to
35 provide each eligible child who has properly applied with a full scholarship as provided by this
36 Part, the Authority shall determine the necessary adjustment of awards consistent with the
37 priority requirements set forth in subsection (c) of this section, including establishing a lottery,
38 awarding scholarships on a pro rata share basis, or both, for the academic year.
39 (c) Award of Funds; Priority. – Beginning May 1 of the year in which the recipient enrolls
40 in an eligible institution, the Authority shall award scholarship funds to students who have
41 properly applied and are otherwise eligible under the Program in the following order:
42 (1) Students who received scholarship funds under Part 2 of Article 14 of Chapter
43 143B of the General Statutes in the previous academic year.
44 (2) Students who received scholarship funds under Part 2 of Article 14 of Chapter
45 143B of the General Statutes in any previous academic year.
46 (3) All other students.
