6 OF HOUSING SLOTS
7 SECTION 9B.9. Of the funds appropriated in this act to the Department of Health
8 and Human Services, the sum of twelve million one hundred ninety-two thousand one hundred
9 twenty-four dollars ($12,192,124) shall be used to meet the requirements contained in the 2012
10 settlement agreement between the State and the United States Department of Justice to ensure
11 that the State will willingly meet the requirements of the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990,
12 section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, and the United States Supreme Court decision in
13 Olmstead v. L.C., 527 U.S. 581 (1999) (the settlement agreement). In order to focus the
14 investment of State funding on meeting the remaining unmet requirements of the settlement
15 agreement, the Department of Health and Human Services is directed to implement a cap on the
16 number of housing slots available through the North Carolina Supportive Housing Program (the
17 program) established under Part 1 of Article 1B of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes.
18 Effective when this act becomes law, the maximum number of slots available through the
19 program shall equal the number of individuals receiving, or approved to receive, a housing slot
20 through the program on the date this act becomes law. In determining whether a housing slot is
21 available for an eligible individual, the Department of Health and Human Services shall give
22 priority placement to individuals who require the housing slot in order for the State to achieve
23 compliance with any requirement of the settlement agreement that has not been discharged by
24 the court. This section shall not be construed to prohibit compliance with the terms of the
25 settlement agreement or any court orders associated with the settlement agreement.
