45 CHILD CARE WORKFORCE PILOT PROGRAM
46 SECTION 9D.11.(a) Of the funds appropriated in this act to the Department of
47 Health and Human Services, Division of Child Development and Early Education, the sum of
48 one million four hundred seventy-six thousand dollars ($1,476,000) in nonrecurring funds for the
49 2025-2026 fiscal year shall be allocated to the North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., to
50 provide the State match for implementing the pilot program described in this section as follows:
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 243

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The sum of nine hundred seventy-two thousand dollars ($972,000) for the
2 2025-2026 fiscal year for the State portion of tuition costs.
3 (2) The sum of five hundred four thousand dollars ($504,000) for the 2025-2026
4 fiscal year for the stipends provided with State funds in accordance with
5 subsection (f) of this section.
6 SECTION 9D.11.(b) Funds described in subsection (a) of this section shall be
7 allocated equally among the local partnerships selected to participate in the pilot program. Local
8 partnerships shall provide documentation of a twenty-five percent (25%) local match as a
9 condition of receiving State funds. Any unexpended and unencumbered funds at the end of the
10 fiscal year from the funds provided under this section shall not revert to the General Fund but
11 shall remain available for use in accordance with this section. Funds provided under this section
12 shall not be used for administrative costs.
13 SECTION 9D.11.(c) The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., in
14 collaboration with the North Carolina Community Colleges System Office, shall develop and
15 implement a two-year pilot program that expands the child care workforce academies currently
16 operating in Johnston and Wayne Counties. The pilot program shall establish child care
17 workforce academies across the State designed to provide free, comprehensive training and
18 support to individuals, with no experience or education in child care, who are interested in
19 pursuing a career in child care.
20 SECTION 9D.11.(d) Local partnerships in the following counties shall participate
21 in the pilot program described under this section: Johnston and Wayne. The North Carolina
22 Partnership for Children, Inc., (NCPC), in collaboration with the Community Colleges System
23 Office, shall select 10 additional local partnerships to participate in the pilot program from the
24 four local partnership regions of the statewide NCPC network, which regions are the West,
25 Mid-West, Mid-East, and East.
26 SECTION 9D.11.(e) The Community Colleges System Office and local community
27 colleges shall coordinate to ensure that graduates of the child care workforce academies meet all
28 requirements to be credentialed with the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential as lead
29 teachers in child care in this State.
30 SECTION 9D.11.(f) Each child care workforce academy (academy) shall seek to
31 enroll no less than 10 students, with a goal of enrolling 15 students in each course. The academy
32 shall operate up to eight hours per day over a two- to three-week period. A participating
33 community college shall strive to offer an academy up to three times per year, with at least one
34 of the three academies occurring at the end of the traditional public school calendar year to allow
35 participation by interested high school and college students. The academy shall be offered
36 free-of-charge to applicants. Students participating in the academy shall receive the knowledge,
37 skills, and training, including the necessary health screenings, background checks, and
38 fingerprinting, required for employment as a lead teacher in a licensed child care program in this
39 State. Upon successful completion of the academy, each student shall receive a North Carolina
40 Early Childhood Credential that will enable the student to begin teaching in a licensed child care
41 program immediately upon graduation. A local partnership may provide each graduate with a
42 one-time stipend. If a one-time stipend for completing the course is provided, the amount shall
43 be at the discretion of the local partnership but shall not be less than one hundred fifty dollars
44 ($150.00). Students shall be eligible to receive an additional one-time stipend in the amount of
45 five hundred dollars ($500.00) in State funds after completing one year of employment as a lead
46 teacher in a licensed child care program in this State.
47 SECTION 9D.11.(g) The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., and local
48 partnerships shall (i) collaborate with the community college in the county or counties in which
49 the local partnership is located, as practicable, to implement the child care workforce academy
50 and (ii) ensure information about the child care workforce academy in the respective county is
51 made available to the public.
