48 EXTEND PRIMARY CARE TASK FORCE
49 SECTION 9E.17.(a) Section 9E.28 of S.L. 2023-134 reads as rewritten:
Page 256 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "SECTION 9E.28.(a) There is established the North Carolina Primary Care Payment
2 Reform Task Force (Task Force) within the Department of Health and Human Services, Division
3 of Health Benefits, for budgetary purposes only.
4 …
5 "SECTION 9E.28.(b) The Task Force established under subsection (a) of this section shall
6 have the following duties:
7 (1) Establish a definition of primary care to be utilized by the Task Force. This
8 term should be applicable to services and care provided under the NC
9 Medicaid program, the State Health Plan, and commercial insurance.
10 (2) Conduct an actuarial evaluation of the current healthcare spend on primary
11 care services, both as it relates to the NC Medicaid program and the
12 commercial market, including Medicare Advantage plans.
13 (3) Determine the adequacy of the primary care delivery system in North
14 Carolina, including the impact this system has on the supply of the primary
15 care providers in this State.
16 (4) Study the primary care payment landscape in other states, specifically
17 considering states that have implemented a minimum primary care spend.
18 (5) Identify data collection and measurement systems to inform creation of a
19 primary care investment target for the NC Medicaid program, the State Health
20 Plan, and commercial insurance. This includes a method by which to measure
21 improvements made toward that target.
22 (5a) Collect and compile data and other information related to healthcare spend on
23 primary care services in a manner that is compliant with the Health Insurance
24 Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 (HIPAA). Within 45 days of a
25 request for data or information from the Task Force, all entities shall comply
26 with the Task Force's request.
27 (6) Evaluate the need for a permanent Primary Care Payment Reform Task Force,
28 or other similar entity, including which State agency or body is best suited to
29 oversee the work of that group.
30 (7) Perform any other studies, evaluations, or determinations the Task Force
31 considers necessary.
32 "SECTION 9E.28.(b1) The Department of Health and Human Services shall develop, and
33 the Task Force and the Department of Health and Human Services shall implement, a detailed
34 data security and safeguarding plan for the data requested pursuant to subsection (b) of this
35 section that includes all of the following:
36 (1) Guidelines for authorizing access to the data, including guidelines for
37 authentication of authorized access.
38 (2) Privacy compliance standards.
39 (3) Privacy and security audits.
40 (4) Breach planning, notification, and procedures.
41 (5) Data retention and disposition policies.
42 (6) Data security policies, including electronic, physical, and administrative
43 safeguards such as data encryption and training of employees.
44 "SECTION 9E.28.(b2) The data collected by the Task Force under subsection (b) of this
45 section, regardless of where it is housed, shall be used only for the purposes of this task force
46 and shall not be considered a public record within the meaning of Chapter 132 of the General
47 Statutes.
48 "SECTION 9E.28.(c) No later than April 1, 2024, and April 1, 2026, the Task Force shall
49 submit a report with its findings and recommendations to the Joint Legislative Oversight
50 Committee on Health and Human Services and the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on
