4 REPLACEMENT FOR CRITICAL IT SYSTEMS THAT SUPPORT SUBSTANCE USE
5 DISORDER PREVENTION AND TREATMENT
6 SECTION 9G.5. The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of
7 Mental Health, Developmental Disabilities, and Substance Use Services (DMH/DD/SUS), shall
8 develop and implement a replacement project for outdated data systems supporting substance use
9 prevention and treatment goals, specifically the Driving While Impaired Services, the Drug
10 Education School, and the Drug Control Unit programs. This replacement project for outdated
11 data systems shall be designed to prevent progression of misuse of substances through education
12 and regulatory supports. The DMH/DD/SUS shall not proceed with this replacement project until
13 the business case has been approved by the Office of State Budget and Management and the State
14 Chief Information Officer in the Enterprise Project Management Office's Touchdown System.
15 Upon approval of the business case, for each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium, the
16 DMH/DD/SUS may budget up to one million two hundred thousand dollars ($1,200,000) of
17 mixed beverage tax receipts available in Budget Code 14460, Budget Fund 134603 for transfer
18 to Budget Code 24410 to implement the replacement project for outdated data systems developed
19 pursuant to this section. Beginning in the fiscal year following project completion, the
20 DMH/DD/SUS may use up to one million two hundred thousand dollars ($1,200,000) of mixed
21 beverage tax receipts each fiscal year to cover operations and maintenance costs for the
22 replacement system.
