32 FEDERAL CHILD SUPPORT INCENTIVE PAYMENTS
33 SECTION 9J.6.(a) Centralized Services. – The North Carolina Child Support
34 Services (NCCSS) Section of the Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Social
35 Services, shall retain up to fifteen percent (15%) of the annual federal incentive payments it
36 receives from the federal government to enhance centralized child support services. To
37 accomplish this requirement, NCCSS shall do the following:
38 (1) In consultation with representatives from county child support services
39 programs, identify how federal incentive funding could improve centralized
40 services.
41 (2) Use federal incentive funds to improve the effectiveness of the State's
42 centralized child support services by supplementing and not supplanting State
43 expenditures for those services.
44 (3) Continue to develop and implement rules that explain the State process for
45 calculating and distributing federal incentive funding to county child support
46 services programs.
47 SECTION 9J.6.(b) County Child Support Services Programs. – NCCSS shall
48 allocate no less than eighty-five percent (85%) of the annual federal incentive payments it
49 receives from the federal government to county child support services programs to improve
50 effectiveness and efficiency using the federal performance measures. To that end, NCCSS shall
51 do the following:
Page 276 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) In consultation with representatives from county child support services
2 programs, examine the current methodology for distributing federal incentive
3 funding to the county programs and determine whether an alternative formula
4 would be appropriate. NCCSS shall use its current formula for distributing
5 federal incentive funding until an alternative formula is adopted.
6 (2) Upon adopting an alternative formula, develop a process to phase in the
7 alternative formula for distributing federal incentive funding over a four-year
8 period.
9 SECTION 9J.6.(c) Reporting by County Child Support Services Programs. –
10 NCCSS shall continue implementing guidelines that identify appropriate uses for federal
11 incentive funding. To ensure those guidelines are properly followed, NCCSS shall require county
12 child support services programs to comply with each of the following:
13 (1) Submit an annual plan describing how federal incentive funding would
14 improve program effectiveness and efficiency as a condition of receiving
15 federal incentive funding.
16 (2) Report annually on the following: (i) how federal incentive funding has
17 improved program effectiveness and efficiency and been reinvested into their
18 programs, (ii) documentation that the funds were spent according to their
19 annual plans, and (iii) any deviations from their plans.
20 SECTION 9J.6.(d) Reporting by NCCSS. – NCCSS shall submit a report on federal
21 child support incentive funding to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and
22 Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division by November 1 of each year. The report shall
23 describe how federal incentive funds enhanced centralized child support services to benefit
24 county child support services programs and improved the effectiveness and efficiency of county
25 child support services programs. The report shall further include any changes to the State process
26 that NCCSS used in calculating and distributing federal incentive funding to county child support
27 services programs and any recommendations for further changes.
28
29 SUCCESSFUL TRANSITION/FOSTER CARE YOUTH
30 SECTION 9J.7. The Foster Care Transitional Living Initiative Fund shall continue
31 to fund and support transitional living services that demonstrate positive outcomes for youth,
32 attract significant private sector funding, and lead to the development of evidence-based
33 programs to serve the at-risk population described in this section. The Fund shall continue to
34 support a demonstration project with services provided by Youth Villages to (i) improve
35 outcomes for youth ages 17-21 years who transition from foster care through implementation of
36 outcome-based Transitional Living Services, (ii) identify cost-savings in social services and
37 juvenile and adult correction services associated with the provision of Transitional Living
38 Services to youth aging out of foster care, and (iii) take necessary steps to establish an
39 evidence-based transitional living program available to all youth aging out of foster care. In
40 continuing to implement these goals, the Foster Care Transitional Living Initiative Fund shall
41 support the following strategies:
42 (1) Transitional Living Services, which is an outcome-based program that follows
43 the Youth Villages Transitional Living Model. Outcomes on more than 7,000
44 participants have been tracked since the program's inception. The program has
45 been evaluated through an independent randomized controlled trial. Results
46 indicate that the Youth Villages Transitional Living Model had positive
47 impacts in a variety of areas, including housing stability, earnings, economic
48 hardship, mental health, and intimate partner violence in comparison to the
49 control population.
50 (2) Public-Private Partnership, which is a commitment by private-sector funding
51 partners to match at least twenty-five percent (25%) of the funds appropriated
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 277

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 to the Foster Care Transitional Living Initiative Fund for the 2025-2027 fiscal
2 biennium for the purposes of providing Transitional Living Services through
3 the Youth Villages Transitional Living Model to youth aging out of foster
4 care.
5 (3) Impact Measurement and Evaluation, which are services funded through
6 private partners to provide independent measurement and evaluation of the
7 impact the Youth Villages Transitional Living Model has on the youth served,
8 the foster care system, and on other programs and services provided by the
9 State which are utilized by former foster care youth.
10 (4) Advancement of Evidence-Based Process, which is the implementation and
11 ongoing evaluation of the Youth Villages Transitional Living Model for the
12 purposes of establishing the first evidence-based transitional living program
13 in the nation. To establish the evidence-based program, additional randomized
14 controlled trials may be conducted to advance the model.
15
16 REPORT ON CERTAIN SNAP AND TANF EXPENDITURES
17 SECTION 9J.8.(a) Funds appropriated in this act to the Department of Health and
18 Human Services, Division of Social Services (Division), for each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal
19 biennium for a report on certain Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) and
20 Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF) expenditures shall be allocated for vendor
21 costs to generate the data regarding expenditures of those programs. The vendor shall generate
22 data to be submitted to the Division that includes, at a minimum, each of the following:
23 (1) The dollar amount and number of transactions accessed or expended
24 out-of-state, by state, for both SNAP benefits and TANF benefits.
25 (2) The amount of benefits expended out-of-state, by state, from active cases for
26 both SNAP and TANF.
27 (3) The dollar amount and number of transactions of benefits accessed or
28 expended in this State, by types of retailers or institutions, for both SNAP and
29 TANF.
30 SECTION 9J.8.(b) Upon receiving the expenditures data for SNAP and TANF from
31 the vendor, the Division shall evaluate the data. After evaluating the expenditures data, the
32 Division shall submit a report on its analysis of the data by June 30 and December 31 of each
33 year to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal
34 Research Division. The Division shall post its report required by this subsection on its website
35 and otherwise make the data available by June 30 and December 31 of each year. In the first
36 report required by this section, the Division shall report how this data is used to investigate fraud
37 and abuse in both SNAP and TANF. The Division shall also report on other types of data and
38 how that data is utilized in the detection of fraud and abuse.
39 SECTION 9J.8.(c) The Division shall maintain the confidentiality of information
40 not public under Chapter 132 of the General Statutes. The Division shall properly redact any
41 information subject to reporting under this section to prevent identification of individual
42 recipients of SNAP or TANF benefits.
43
44 CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER FUNDS
45 SECTION 9J.9. At least seventy-five percent (75%) of the funds appropriated in
46 this act to the Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Social Services, for
47 Children's Advocacy Centers of North Carolina, Inc. (CACNC), a nonprofit organization, for
48 each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium shall be distributed to child advocacy centers in this
49 State that are in good standing with CACNC in accordance with the requirements of
50 G.S. 108A-77.2.
