17 SECTION 11.1.(i) Rural Community Development. – Funds allocated for the Rural
18 Community Development Category in subsection (a) of this section shall be made available as
19 grants for eligible activities listed in this subsection. These funds shall provide grants that support
20 community development and comprehensive growth projects to be awarded by the Department
21 of Commerce. The Rural Community Development Category will provide grants to units of local
22 government in development tier one and development tier two areas, as defined in
23 G.S. 143B-437.08, and in rural census tracts, as defined in G.S. 143B-472.127(a)(2), in any other
24 area to support projects that promote broad-based community development activities, increased
25 local investment and economic growth, and stronger and more viable rural neighborhoods. In
26 awarding grants under this section, preference shall be given to projects in development tier one
27 areas, as defined in G.S. 143B-437.08. The funds available for grants under this category may be
28 used for all of the following, subject to the national objectives and eligible activities allowed
29 under guidance issued by HUD:
30 (1) Essential repairs to prevent abandonment and deterioration of housing in
31 low- and moderate-income neighborhoods.
32 (2) Public improvements, including parks, streets, sidewalks, and water and sewer
33 lines.
34 (3) Public facilities, including neighborhood and community facilities and
35 facilities for individuals with special needs.
36 (4) Public services, including employment, crime prevention, and energy
37 conservation.
38 (5) Assistance to private, for-profit entities for economic development.
39 (6) Technical assistance to public or nonprofit entities for neighborhood
40 revitalization or economic development activities.
41 (7) Assistance to for-profit and nonprofit entities to facilitate economic
42 development activities.
43 SECTION 11.1.(j) Deobligated Funds. – Throughout each year, deobligated funds
44 arise in the various funding categories and program years of the Community Development Block
45 Grant (CDBG) program as a result of (i) projects coming in under budget, (ii) projects being
46 canceled, or (iii) projects being required to repay funds. Surplus federal administrative funds in
47 the CDBG program may vary from year to year based upon the amount of State-appropriated
48 funds allocated and the amount of eligible in-kind funds identified. To allow the Department of
49 Commerce and the Department of Environmental Quality to quickly deploy deobligated and
50 surplus federal administrative funds as they are identified throughout the program year, the
Page 298 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 following shall apply to the use of deobligated CDBG funds and surplus federal administrative
2 funds:
3 (1) All surplus federal administrative funds shall be divided proportionally
4 between the Departments of Commerce and Environmental Quality and shall
5 be used as provided in subdivisions (2) and (3) of this subsection.
6 (2) All deobligated funds allocated to the Department of Commerce and any
7 surplus federal administrative funds, as provided for in subdivision (1) of this
8 subsection, may be used by the Department for all of the following:
9 a. To issue grants in the CDBG Economic Development or
10 Neighborhood Revitalization Program Category.
11 b. For providing training and guidance to local governments relative to
12 the CDBG program, its management, and administrative requirements.
13 c. For any other purpose consistent with the Department's administration
14 of the CDBG program if an equal amount of State matching funds is
15 available.
16 (3) All deobligated funds allocated to the Department of Environmental Quality
