22 SECTION 12.6.(b) Part 8E of Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes, as
23 enacted by subsection (a) of this section, reads as rewritten:
24 "Part 8E. Beach and Inlet Management Planning.
25 "§ 143-215.73N. Findings.
26 The General Assembly makes the following findings:
27 (1) North Carolina has 320 miles of ocean beach, including some of the most
28 pristine and attractive beaches in the country.
29 (2) The balance between economic development and quality of life in North
30 Carolina has made our coast one of the most desirable along the Atlantic
31 Seaboard.
32 (3) North Carolina's beaches are vital to the State's tourism industry.
33 (4) North Carolina's beaches belong to all the State's citizens and provide
34 recreational and economic benefits to our residents statewide.
35 (5) Beach erosion can threaten the economic viability of coastal communities and
36 can significantly affect State tax revenues.
37 (6) The Atlantic Seaboard is vulnerable to hurricanes and other coastal storms,
38 and it is prudent to take precautions such as beach nourishment that protect
39 and conserve the State's beaches and reduce property damage and flooding.
40 (7) Beach renourishment as an erosion control method provides hurricane flood
41 protection, enhances the attractiveness of beaches to tourists, restores habitat
42 for turtles, shorebirds, and plants, and provides additional public access to
43 beaches.
44 (8) Federal policy previously favored and assisted voluntary movement of
45 structures threatened by erosion, but this assistance is no longer available.
46 (9) Relocation of structures threatened by erosion is sometimes the best available
47 remedy for the property owner and is in the public interest.
48 (10) Public parking and public access areas are needed for use by the general public
49 to enable their enjoyment of North Carolina's beaches.
50 (11) Acquisition of high erosion hazard property by local or State agencies can
51 reduce risk to citizens and property, reduce costs to insurance policyholders,
Page 304 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 improve public access to beaches and waterways, and protect the
2 environment.
3 (12) Beach nourishment projects such as those at Wrightsville Beach and Carolina
4 Beach have been very successful and greatly reduced property damage during
5 Hurricane Fran.hurricanes and other coastal storms that have impacted the
6 State's coast.
7 (13) Because local beach communities derive the primary benefits from the
8 presence of adequate beaches, a program of beach management and
9 restoration should not be accomplished without a commitment of local funds
10 to combat the problem of beach erosion.
11 (14) The With limited exceptions, the State of North Carolina prohibits seawalls
12 and hardening the shoreline to prevent destroying the public's beaches.
13 (15) Beach nourishment is encouraged by both the Coastal Resources Commission
14 and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers as a method to control beach erosion.
15 (16) The Department of Environment and Natural Resources Environmental
16 Quality has statutory authority to assist local governments in financing beach
17 nourishment projects and is the sponsor of several federal navigation projects
18 that result in dredging beach-quality sand.
19 (17) It is declared to be a necessary governmental responsibility to properly
20 manage and protect North Carolina's beaches from erosion and that good
21 planning is needed to assure a cost-effective and equitable approach to beach
22 management and restoration, and that as part of a comprehensive response to
23 beach erosion, sound policies are needed to facilitate the ability of landowners
24 to move threatened structures and to allow public acquisition of appropriate
25 parcels of land for public beach access.
26 "§ 143-215.73O. Beach and inlet management plan.
27 (a) The Department of Environment and Natural Resources Environmental Quality shall
28 compile and evaluate information on the current conditions and erosion rates of beaches, on
29 coastal geology, and on storm and erosion hazards for use in developing a State plan and strategy
30 for beach management and restoration. The Department of Environment and Natural Resources
31 Environmental Quality shall make this information available to local governments for use in
32 land-use planning.
33 (b) The Department of Environment and Natural Resources shall develop a multiyear
34 beach management and restoration strategy and plan that does all of the following:
35 (1) Utilizes the data and expertise available in the Divisions of Water Resources,
36 Coastal Management, and Energy, Mineral, and Land Resources.
37 (2) Identifies the erosion rate at each beach community and estimates the degree
38 of vulnerability to storm and hurricane damage.
39 (3) Uses the best available geological and geographical information to determine
40 the need for and probable effectiveness of beach nourishment.
41 (4) Provides for coordination with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, the North
42 Carolina Department of Transportation, the North Carolina Division of
43 Emergency Management, and other State and federal agencies concerned with
44 beach management issues.
45 (5) Provides a status report on all U.S. Army Corps of Engineers' beach protection
46 projects in the planning, construction, or operational stages.
47 (6) Makes maximum feasible use of suitable sand dredged from navigation
48 channels for beach nourishment to avoid the loss of this resource and to reduce
49 equipment mobilization costs.
50 (7) Promotes inlet sand bypassing where needed to replicate the natural flow of
51 sand interrupted by inlets.
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 305

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (8) Provides for geological and environmental assessments to locate suitable
2 materials for beach nourishment.
3 (9) Considers the regional context of beach communities to determine the most
4 cost-effective approach to beach nourishment.
5 (10) Provides for and requires adequate public beach access, including
6 handicapped access.
7 (11) Recommends priorities for State funding for beach nourishment projects,
8 based on the amount of erosion occurring, the potential damage to property
9 and to the economy, the benefits for recreation and tourism, the adequacy of
10 public access, the availability of local government matching funds, the status
11 of project planning, the adequacy of project engineering, the
12 cost-effectiveness of the project, and the environmental impacts.
13 (11a) Includes a four-year cycle of planned maintenance and resiliency projects for
14 the State's beaches and inlets.
15 (12) Includes recommendations on obtaining the maximum available federal
16 financial assistance for beach nourishment.
17 (13) Is subject to a public hearing to receive citizen input.
18 (c) Each plan shall be as complete as resources and available information allow. The
19 Department of Environment and Natural Resources Environmental Quality shall revise the plan
20 every two years and shall submit the revised plan to the General Assembly no later than March
21 1 of each odd-numbered year. The Department may issue a supplement to the plan in
22 even-numbered years if significant new information becomes available.
23 "§ 143-215.73P. Federal funds; matching.
24 In the event that federal funds become available for planning and developing shore protection
25 projects, the State shall match those funds in accordance with the funding guidelines set out in
26 G.S. 143-215.71."
