10 MORATORIUM ON ISSUANCE OF CERTIFICATES FOR CERTAIN SURFACE
11 WATER TRANSFERS
12 SECTION 12.16.(a) Findings. – The General Assembly finds that the State's laws
13 regulating surface water transfers, originally enacted more than 30 years ago, should be
14 comprehensively reviewed and evaluated for updates in light of the State's tremendous economic
15 and population growth and the impact of natural disasters on riverine and water reservoir systems
16 over that period. In particular, the General Assembly finds that the approval of proposed transfers
17 that are significant in terms of their size compared to the overall hydrologic flow, current and
18 future water storage capacity, and cumulative water resources demands within the source river
19 basin should be temporarily paused while this review and evaluation is ongoing.
20 SECTION 12.16.(b) Study. – The North Carolina Collaboratory at the University of
21 North Carolina at Chapel Hill (Collaboratory) shall study the current statutory process for
22 approval of surface water transfers and provide any recommendations for legislation revising that
23 process that the Collaboratory finds is needed. As part of its study, the Collaboratory shall review
24 all of the following:
25 (1) The adequacy of the requirements for an environmental impact study set forth
26 in G.S. 143-215.22L(d) in ensuring that all impacts on upstream and
27 downstream users of water in the river basin are comprehensively and
28 equitably compiled and considered.
29 (2) Whether the information on which the Environmental Management
30 Commission (EMC) bases final certification decisions adequately takes into
31 account (i) issues of economic equity for lower income and lower population
32 communities in the source river basin that would experience potential impacts
33 on future economic growth due to the proposed transfer, (ii) negative impacts
34 of increases in water pollutant concentration caused by large surface water
35 transfers on riverine ecosystems, and (iii) whether the denial of the surface
36 transfer request would result in a substantial increase in utility rates or
37 otherwise cause a financial hardship due to alternative infrastructure
38 construction costs for the requesting party.
39 (3) Changes to the process needed to reflect the impact of recent climate trends
40 that impact the range of water flows in the State's mainstem rivers during
41 periods of extreme heat, drought, or flooding events.
42 (4) How to build into the certification process incentives for parties requesting
43 surface water transfers to implement land use, infrastructure, and drought
44 resiliency policies that will reduce the size of transfers needed to meet future
45 water demands.
46 (5) Any other matters the Collaboratory deems relevant to its efforts to increase
47 the fairness and effectiveness of the surface water transfer certification
48 requirements.
49 SECTION 12.16.(c) Consultation. – In conducting the study required by subsection
50 (b) of this section, the Collaboratory will consult with the Army Corps of Engineers and other
51 private or public entities with management responsibilities over water impoundments with
Page 316 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 respect to the impact of significant surface water transfers, as defined in subsection (e) of this
2 section, on those impoundments continuing to meet their present levels and future projected
3 needs for hydroelectric power generation and water supply.
4 SECTION 12.16.(d) Report. – By January 1, 2027, the Collaboratory shall report its
5 findings, along with any legislative recommendations, to the Joint Legislative Oversight
6 Committee on Agriculture and Natural and Economic Resources.
7 SECTION 12.16.(e) Moratorium on Certain Surface Water Transfer Certificates. –
8 In order to permit sufficient time for the General Assembly to complete the study, the EMC shall
9 not issue a certificate authorizing a significant new surface water transfer or a significant increase
10 in an existing surface water transfer until the end of the moratorium provided in this section. The
11 moratorium in this section shall end six months after the submission of the report required by
12 subsection (d) of this section. For purposes of this section, a proposed new or increased surface
13 water transfer is significant if it would result in a total increase in transfer between river basins,
14 as defined in G.S. 143-215.22G, in excess of 15,000,000 gallons per day.
15 SECTION 12.16.(f) This section is effective when it becomes law.
