44 DISPOSITION
45 SECTION 16.16B.(a) Chapter 50 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a
46 new Article to read:
47 "Article 6.
48 "Complex Family Financial Cases.
49 "§ 50-110. Definitions.
50 The following definitions shall apply in this Article:
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 333

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge. – A Complex Family Financial
2 Court Judge designated by the Chief Justice of the North Carolina Supreme
3 Court as provided for in G.S. 7A-45.1(a14) who determines which cases are
4 designated as complex family financial cases, assigns all cases designated as
5 complex family financial cases, and prepares any required reports in addition
6 to conducting hearings and entering orders in their assigned complex family
7 financial cases.
8 (2) Complex family financial case. – Any claim or claims approved for hearing
9 as a complex family financial case as provided for by this Article. Claims
10 eligible for hearing as a complex family financial case are equitable
11 distribution, alimony, post separation support, child support, or any
12 combination of those claims.
13 (3) Complex Family Financial Court Judge. – A special superior court judge
14 appointed pursuant to G.S. 7A-45.1(a14) to hear and enter orders in complex
15 family financial cases filed in district court.
16 "§ 50-111. Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
17 To serve as a Complex Family Financial Court Judge, the individual must meet the following
18 minimum qualifications:
19 (1) Attorney licensed in North Carolina and in good standing with the North
20 Carolina State Bar.
21 (2) Substantial involvement handling complex family financial cases during the
22 10 calendar years prior to the year of application, including the following:
23 a. Average at least 600 hours per year handling complex family financial
24 cases.
25 b. No less than 400 hours handling complex family financial cases in any
26 one year.
27 (3) During the five calendar years prior to the application:
28 a. Completed at least 45 hours of continuing legal education credits in
29 family law, nine of which may be in related fields, including taxation,
30 trial advocacy, evidence, negotiation, including training in mediation,
31 arbitration, and collaborative law, real property, estate planning and
32 probate law, trusts, business organizations, employee benefits,
33 bankruptcy, and immigration law. Only nine hours will be recognized
34 for attendance at an extended negotiation or mediation training course.
35 Parenting coordinator training will not qualify for family law or related
36 field hours.
37 b. A minimum of six hours continuing legal education must have been
38 completed in each of those five years.
39 (4) Satisfactory peer review by 10 lawyers or judges who are identified by the
40 applicant. The identified individuals must have personal knowledge of the
41 competence and qualification of the applicant in handling complex family
42 financial matters at the pretrial, trial, and posttrial level. All identified
43 individuals must be licensed and in good standing to practice law in the State
44 of North Carolina. No identified individual may be related by blood or
45 marriage to the applicant nor be a colleague at the applicant's place of
46 employment at the time of the application.
47 "§ 50-112. Authority and duties of a Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
48 (a) A Complex Family Financial Court Judge under this Article has the following
49 authority and responsibilities in all complex family financial cases in district court:
50 (1) To conduct hearings and to ensure that the parties' due process rights are
51 protected.
Page 334 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) To take testimony and establish a record.
2 (3) To evaluate evidence and make decisions regarding the issues being heard.
3 (4) To enter temporary, interim, and final orders related to the issues being heard.
4 (5) To enter orders granting or denying any motion filed under G.S. 1A-1 or any
5 local rules of court for the county in which the action was filed related to
6 actions under this Chapter.
7 (6) To subpoena witnesses and documents.
8 (b) A Complex Family Financial Court Judge is authorized to conduct hearings in district
9 court on complex family financial cases statewide.
10 (c) A Complex Family Financial Court Judge must complete at least nine hours of
11 continuing legal education credits in family law or related fields each year, including taxation,
12 trial advocacy, evidence, negotiation (including training in mediation, arbitration, and
13 collaborative law), real property, estate planning and probate law, trusts, business organizations,
14 employee benefits, bankruptcy, and immigration law. Only one hour per year will be recognized
15 for attendance at negotiation or mediation training, and parenting coordinator training will not
16 qualify for family law or related field hours.
17 "§ 50-113. Designation of a complex family financial claim.
18 (a) A party designating a claim as a complex family financial claim shall file a Notice of
19 Designation in the district court in which the action has been filed and shall contemporaneously
20 serve the notice on all parties or counsel and on the Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
21 The Notice of Designation shall, in good faith and based on information reasonably available,
22 succinctly state each applicable factor provided in G.S. 50-114, the reasons supporting each
23 factor for designation as a complex family financial claim, and any other information supporting
24 designation as a complex family financial claim. Any factor or reasons supporting the designation
25 not asserted shall be deemed conclusively waived.
26 (b) Within 30 days after service of the Notice of Designation, any other party may, in
27 good faith, file and serve an opposition to the designation of the claim as a complex family
28 financial claim. The opposition to the designation of the claim shall assert all reasons for which
29 the party opposing designation objects to the designation, and any reason not asserted shall be
30 deemed conclusively waived. The opposition to the designation shall be served on each opposing
31 party and the Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge and shall be filed in the district court
32 in which the action has been filed.
33 (c) A family court judge assigned to the case may request designation of pending family
34 financial claims as complex family financial claims by following the procedure in subsection (a)
35 of this section. If the judicial district does not have a designated family court, the chief district
36 court judge for the judicial district may request the designation. Any party to the action may file
37 and serve opposition to the request for designation as provided for in subsection (b) of this
38 section.
39 (d) Based on the written Notice of Designation and any opposition filed, the Chief
40 Complex Family Financial Court Judge shall determine whether the action should be designated
41 as a complex family financial claim by written order entered within 45 days of service of the
42 Notice of Designation.
43 (e) Each party shall pay equal shares of the additional filing fee as required under
44 G.S. 7A-305. Only one additional filing fee shall be required per complex family financial case.
45 (f) Once an order granting designation of a claim as a complex family financial claim is
46 entered, that claim shall be designated and administered as a complex family financial case and
47 assigned to a Complex Family Financial Court Judge by the Chief Complex Family Financial
48 Court Judge. All proceedings related to the claims designated as a complex family financial claim
49 shall be before the Complex Family Financial Court Judge to whom the complex family financial
50 case has been assigned. If any complex family financial claim status is denied, the claim or claims
51 to which the designation was denied shall be heard with any other claims filed under this Chapter.
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 335

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (g) Complex family financial cases are subject to all provisions of Article 1 of this
2 Chapter, the North Carolina Rules of Civil Procedure, the North Carolina Rules of Evidence, any
3 applicable local rules of court for the county in which the complex family financial case is
4 pending, and any rules which may be adopted by the Chief Justice of the North Carolina Supreme
5 Court.
6 "§ 50-114. Factors for complex family financial case determination.
7 The Chief Complex Family Financial Court Judge shall consider each of the following factors
8 in determining whether a claim or claims shall be designated as a complex family financial case:
9 (1) Valuation and classification issues related to trusts, including active and
10 passive increases or decreases in value.
11 (2) Valuation and classification issues related to businesses, including active or
12 passive increases or decreases in value.
13 (3) Valuation and classification of real property, including active or passive
14 increases or decreases in value.
15 (4) Valuation and classification issues regarding complex retirement or other
16 employment benefits, including employee stock ownership plans, stock
17 options, profit sharing, defined contribution plans, and defined benefit plans.
18 (5) Valuation and classification of profits, bonuses, or other income or assets
19 received after the date of separation.
20 (6) Active or passive changes in value to separate property during the marriage.
21 (7) Tax issues arising from the distribution of assets and debts, including tax loss
22 carryforwards, refunds, credits, or tax consequences.
23 (8) Whether there are loans or transfers between businesses or shareholders.
24 (9) Whether there are third-party defendants.
25 (10) Validity of a premarital or property settlement agreement pled in defense to
26 an equitable distribution, alimony, post separation support, or child support
27 case.
28 (11) Total value of real and personal property.
29 (12) Calculation of income for spousal support, child support, or both when income
30 includes non W-2 income.
31 (13) Total length of time requested for trial on the issues detailed on the Notice of
32 Designation.
33 Claims which have been filed in excess of 365 days shall be given priority over claims filed
34 less than 365 days, and requested trial dates for the complex family financial case in excess of
35 15 days shall be given priority.
36 "§ 50-115. Complex family financial hearings.
37 (a) Motion hearings shall be held virtually unless the assigned judge determines good
38 cause exists to hold the hearing in person. If an in-person hearing is ordered, it shall be held at
39 the courthouse in the county in which the action was filed in an available district or superior
40 courtroom staffed by a deputy or assistant clerk and bailiff.
41 (b) Hearings on the issues designated as a complex family financial case shall be held in
42 person at the courthouse in the county in which the action was filed in an available district or
43 superior courtroom staffed by a deputy or assistant clerk and bailiff.
44 (c) All complex family financial hearings must be recorded and exhibits maintained as
45 required for any other matter.
46 (d) Any hearing on final disposition of the complex family financial case must be
47 scheduled on consecutive days.
48 "§ 50-116. Appeal from orders of the Complex Family Financial Court Judge.
49 Appeals of orders entered by a Complex Family Financial Court Judge shall be as provided
50 for in G.S. 7A-27(b)."
