4 public through electronic means, including the Internet. The agency shall identify any inhibitors
5 to electronic transactions between the agency and the public, including legal, policy, financial,
6 or privacy concerns and specific inhibitors unique to the agency or type of transaction. An agency
7 shall not provide a transaction through the Internet that is impractical, unreasonable, or not
8 permitted by laws pertaining to privacy or security.
9 (b) An agency may charge a fee to cover its costs of permitting a person to complete a
10 transaction through the World Wide Web internet or other means of electronic access. The
11 transaction fee may be applied on a per transaction basis and may be calculated either as a flat
12 fee or a percentage fee, as determined under an agreement between a person and a public agency.
13 The fee may be collected by the agency or by its third party agent.fee. Neither the flat fee nor the
14 percentage fee shall exceed two percent (2%) of the total amount of each transaction. An agency
15 shall not charge a surcharge for accepting electronic payments. For purposes of this subsection,
16 the following definitions apply:
17 (1) Surcharge. – A fee added to a payment by charge card, credit card, debit card,
18 or by electronic funds transfer for the convenience of making the electronic
19 payment or for any other purpose not authorized by law.
20 (2) Transaction fee. – A fee charged by a payment processor to a State agency for
21 processing a charge card, credit card, or debit card payment.
22 (c) The fee flat fee or percentage fee imposed under subsection (b) of this section must
23 be approved by the State Chief Information Officer. The revenue derived from the fee must be
24 credited to a nonreverting agency reserve account. The funds in the account may be expended
25 only for e-commerce initiatives and projects approved by the State Chief Information Officer.
26 For purposes of this subsection, the term "public agencies" does not include a county, unit, special
27 district, or other political subdivision of government. The State Chief Information Officer shall
28 report any fees imposed under subsection (b) of this section and expenditures for e-commerce
29 initiatives and projects to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations and the
30 Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Information Technology.
31 (d) This section does not apply to the Judicial Department."
