30 SECTION 38.2.(b) Part 4 of Article 6 of Chapter 147 of the General Statutes, as
31 created and amended by Section 38.1 of this act, reads as rewritten:
32 "Part 4. North Carolina Investment Authority.
33 "§ 147-70.1. Creation of Investment Authority.
34 (a) Creation. – The North Carolina Investment Authority is created as a body corporate
35 and politic having the powers and jurisdiction as provided under this Article or any other law.
36 The Investment Authority is a State agency for the performance of essential governmental and
37 public functions. The Investment Authority is located within, but independent from the control
38 of, the Department of State Treasurer. The Investment Authority shall have perpetual succession.
39 (b) Independence. – The Investment Authority, in carrying out its statutory
40 responsibilities, shall be independent of any fiscal control exercised by the Director of the
41 Budget, the Department of Administration, and the Department of State Treasurer, including for
42 organizational, staffing, procurement, and budgetary purposes. Except as provided under
43 subsection (c) of this section and unless otherwise explicitly provided by law, the Investment
44 Authority is exempt from the State Budget Act, and the provisions of Chapter 143C of the
45 General Statutes do not apply to the Investment Authority.
46 (c) Fiduciary Funds. – In order for the Investment Authority to effectively operate the
47 investment programs under its management, all funds while under management of the Investment
48 Authority are Fiduciary Funds described under subdivisions (8) through (10) of G.S. 143C-1-3(a)
49 and shall be accounted for as specified in G.S. 147-69.3(f).
50 "§ 147-70.2. Powers and duties of the Investment Authority.
Page 426 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) In addition to the authority granted to the Investment Authority under this Article or
2 any other law, the Investment Authority shall have all of the powers necessary to execute the
3 provisions of this Part, including, at a minimum, the following powers:
4 (1) The right to sue and be sued.
5 (2) To take, demand, receive, and possess all kinds of real and personal property
6 necessary and proper for its purposes.
7 (3) To bargain, sell, grant, alienate, or dispose of all real and personal property as
8 it may lawfully acquire.
9 (b) The Investment Authority shall have the right to acquire fidelity bonds, fiduciary
10 insurance, directors' and officers' insurance, or errors and omissions coverage, as determined by
11 the Investment Authority board. This right is independent of any purchase of insurance by the
12 State Treasurer under G.S. 147-67.1.
13 (c) Pursuant to G.S. 143B-1320(b), the Investment Authority shall be exempt from the
14 provisions of Article 15 of Chapter 143B of the General Statutes.
15 "§ 147-70.3. Taxation of Investment Authority.
16 (a) Property owned or acquired by the Authority is exempt from all taxes imposed by the
17 State or any political subdivision of the State.
18 (b) The Investment Authority shall not be subject to State income taxes.
19 (c) This section shall not be construed to apply in any way to individual members of the
20 Board of Directors or any employee of the Investment Authority.
21 "§ 147-70.4. Confidentiality of Investment Authority records.
22 Any record or other information received or generated by the Investment Authority in order
23 to negotiate at arm's length investment transactions that constitute a trade secret, as defined in
24 G.S. 66-152, is not public record and is exempt from the requirements of Chapter 132 of the
25 General Statutes until the applicable negotiation is completed and unless the record or
26 information substantiates a conflict with the duties of the Investment Authority under
27 G.S. 147-70.6(a).
28 "§ 147-70.5. Criminal record checks.
29 (a) The Investment Authority may obtain from the State and National Repositories of
30 Criminal Histories or from any other lawful source the criminal history of any of the following
31 individuals:
32 (1) A current or prospective permanent or temporary employee of the Investment
33 Authority.
34 (2) A contractor with the Investment Authority.
35 (3) An employee or agent of a contractor with the Investment Authority who is
36 performing or will perform work for the Investment Authority.
37 (4) A volunteer of the Investment Authority.
38 (5) Any other individual otherwise engaged by the Investment Authority who will
39 have access to health or financial information or data maintained by the
40 Investment Authority that is confidential or otherwise nonpublic.
41 (b) The Investment Authority may deny employment to or dismiss any individual
42 identified under subdivisions (1), (2), (4), and (5) of subsection (a) of this section who refuses to
43 consent to a criminal history record check or to the use of fingerprints or other identifying
44 information required by the State or National Repositories of Criminal Histories. Any refusal
45 shall constitute just cause for the employment denial or the dismissal from employment.
46 (c) The Investment Authority may extend a conditional offer of employment pending the
47 results of a criminal history record check authorized by this section.
