21 DMV LICENSE RENEWAL PRIVATIZATION PILOT PROGRAM
22 SECTION 43.17.(a) Intent. – It is the intent of the General Assembly to evaluate the
23 feasibility, efficiency, customer service impact, and cost-effectiveness of allowing private
24 entities to perform certain functions traditionally administered by the Division of Motor Vehicles
25 of the Department of Transportation (DMV) by implementing pilot programs in Guilford and
26 Harnett Counties authorizing certain third-party vendors to provide drivers license renewal
27 services.
28 SECTION 43.17.(b) RFP Issuance. – No later than January 1, 2026, the DMV shall
29 issue a Request for Proposals (RFP) to solicit bids from third-party vendors to provide renewal
30 services for Class C regular drivers licenses in Guilford and Harnett Counties. The RFP shall
31 require that proposals include, at minimum, the following information:
32 (1) A description of the systems the third-party vendor will implement to comply
33 with:
34 a. All federal requirements and the requirements of Chapter 20 of the
35 General Statutes.
36 b. The DMV's data security protocols.
37 (2) The minimum requirements the third-party vendor will impose for personnel
38 and facilities.
39 (3) Plans for maintaining financial sustainability while providing drivers license
40 renewal services at a cost that does not exceed any fee established by Chapter
41 20 of the General Statutes.
42 (4) A description of performance benchmarks, including, but not limited to,
43 provisions for customer service evaluation and customer complaint resolution,
44 and a plan for submitting quarterly written reports to the DMV evaluating
45 compliance with those benchmarks.
46 (5) A plan for transitioning back to DMV's provision of drivers license renewal
47 services if the pilot program is not continued.
48 SECTION 43.17.(c) Contract Awards and Duration. – No later than July 1, 2026,
49 the DMV shall award one or more contracts to third-party vendors in Guilford and Harnett
50 Counties. The duration of a contract may not extend beyond January 1, 2029.
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 505

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 43.17.(d) Pilot Program Implementation Date and Requirements. – The
2 pilot program shall begin January 1, 2027, and, notwithstanding any other provision of law, the
3 selected third-party vendors are authorized to issue renewed Class C regular drivers licenses on
4 or after that date. No third-party vendor shall issue a renewed license unless the license meets all
5 of the requirements for renewal pursuant to federal law and Chapter 20 of the General Statutes.
6 A third-party vendor shall not charge any fee for renewal in excess of the fee established by
7 statute.
8 SECTION 43.17.(e) Third-Party Vendor Reporting Requirements. – Each
9 third-party vendor contracting with the DMV pursuant to this section shall quarterly submit a
10 written report to the DMV evaluating compliance with the performance benchmarks established
11 in the RFP.
12 SECTION 43.17.(f) DMV Oversight. – The DMV shall provide oversight of the
13 pilot program, including periodic audits, and may terminate or suspend the participation of any
14 third-party vendor for noncompliance with the General Statutes or any other program
15 requirements, including, but not limited to, unsatisfactory customer service or customer
16 complaint resolution.
17 SECTION 43.17.(g) DMV Reporting Requirements. – The DMV shall submit a first
18 report no later than December 31, 2027, and a second report no later than December 31, 2028, to
19 the Joint Legislative Transportation Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division. The
20 reports shall evaluate the pilot program, and, at minimum, include:
21 (1) The number of renewals processed by third-party vendors.
22 (2) An evaluation of each third-party vendor's performance benchmarks.
23 (3) A cost-benefit and efficiency analysis.
24 (4) A description of all audit results.
25 (5) Recommendations regarding the continuation, expansion, or termination of
26 privatized renewal services, including a plan for transitioning back to DMV
27 provision of drivers license renewal services if the pilot program is not
28 continued.
29 SECTION 43.17.(h) State-Offered Services During Pilot Program. – Nothing in this
30 section limits the authority of State-operated DMV offices to provide drivers license renewal
31 services in Guilford and Harnett Counties.
32 SECTION 43.17.(i) Sunset. – This section expires January 1, 2029.
33
34 DMV IN-HOME LICENSE RENEWAL PILOT PROGRAM
35 SECTION 43.18.(a) Intent. – It is the intent of the General Assembly to improve the
36 accessibility of and customer service provided by the Division of Motor Vehicles of the
37 Department of Transportation (DMV) by implementing a pilot program in Forsyth County
38 authorizing either the DMV or certain third-party vendors to provide in-home drivers license
39 renewal services. For purposes of this section, the term "in-home drivers license renewal service"
40 means a process by which personnel, employed either by the DMV or a third-party vendor
41 authorized by the DMV, travel to a license holder's residence to conduct the necessary procedures
42 for drivers license renewal.
43 SECTION 43.18.(b) RFP Issuance. – No later than January 1, 2026, the DMV shall
44 issue a Request for Proposals (RFP) to solicit bids from third-party vendors to provide in-home
45 drivers license renewal services for Class C regular drivers licenses in Forsyth County. The RFP
46 shall require that proposals include, at minimum, the following information:
47 (1) A description of the systems the third-party vendor will implement to comply
48 with:
49 a. All federal requirements and the requirements of Chapter 20 of the
50 General Statutes.
51 b. The DMV's data security protocols.
Page 506 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The minimum requirements the third-party vendor will impose for personnel
2 and facilities.
3 (3) Plans for acquiring access to the software and equipment necessary to provide
4 in-home drivers license services.
5 (4) Plans for maintaining financial sustainability.
6 (5) A description of performance benchmarks, including, but not limited to,
7 provisions for customer service evaluation and customer complaint resolution,
8 and a plan for submitting quarterly written reports to the DMV evaluating
9 compliance with those benchmarks.
10 SECTION 43.18.(c) Contract Awards and Duration. – No later than July 1, 2026,
11 the DMV shall award one or more contracts to third-party vendors in Forsyth County. The
12 duration of a contract may not extend beyond January 1, 2029.
13 SECTION 43.18.(d) Pilot Program Implementation Date and Requirements. – The
14 pilot program shall begin January 1, 2027, and, notwithstanding any other provision of law, the
15 selected third-party vendors are authorized to provide in-home drivers license renewal services
16 for Class C regular drivers licenses to residents of Forsyth County on or after that date. No
17 third-party vendor shall issue a renewed license unless the license meets all of the requirements
18 for renewal pursuant to federal law and Chapter 20 of the General Statutes.
19 SECTION 43.18.(e) Fees. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law, either the
20 DMV or a third-party vendor providing in-home drivers license renewal services may charge a
21 fee of up to double the fee set by Chapter 20 of the General Statutes for the issuance of a renewed
22 license.
