29 third-party vendor for noncompliance with the General Statutes or any other program
30 requirements, including, but not limited to, unsatisfactory customer service or customer
31 complaint resolution.
32 SECTION 43.18.(h) DMV Reporting Requirements. – The DMV shall submit a first
33 report no later than December 31, 2027, and a second report no later than December 31, 2028, to
34 the Joint Legislative Transportation Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division. The
35 reports shall evaluate the pilot program, and, at minimum, include:
36 (1) The number of in-home renewals processed by third-party vendors.
37 (2) An evaluation of each third-party vendor's performance benchmarks.
38 (3) A cost-benefit and efficiency analysis.
39 (4) A description of all audit results.
40 (5) Recommendations regarding the continuation, expansion, or termination of
41 privatized in-home renewal services.
42 SECTION 43.18.(i) State-Offered Services During Pilot Program. – Nothing in this
43 section limits the authority of State-operated DMV offices to provide drivers license renewal
44 services, including in-home drivers license renewal services, in Forsyth County.
45 SECTION 43.18.(j) Sunset. – This section expires January 1, 2029.
46
47 PILOT PROGRAM TO ALLOW COMMERCIAL DRIVER TRAINING SCHOOLS TO
48 ADMINISTER EXAMINATIONS REQUIRED FOR DRIVERS LICENSING
49 SECTION 43.19.(a) The Division of Motor Vehicles shall develop a pilot program
50 to authorize commercial driver training schools licensed under Article 14 of Chapter 20 of the
51 General Statutes to additionally administer all examinations required for drivers licensing and
Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition Page 507

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 permitting in accordance with G.S. 20-7, 20-11, and 20-37.13. The Division's plan for
2 implementation of the pilot program shall include all of the following:
3 (1) The Division shall select at least two but not more than five counties in diverse
4 geographic regions in which to implement the pilot program.
5 (2) Commercial driver training schools must offer the same examinations as those
6 administered by the Division, using the same scoring methods and standards,
7 and must administer examinations in compliance with all applicable State and
8 federal requirements.
9 (3) Examinations may be offered by participating commercial driver training
10 schools outside of standard Division office hours on any day of the week.
11 (4) The Division shall develop a process for a prospective licensee to demonstrate
12 successful completion of an examination administered by a commercial driver
13 training school, whereby documentation may be provided to the prospective
14 licensee or submitted directly to the Division by the school administering the
15 examination.
16 (5) Upon successful completion of examinations required for licensing or
17 permitting administered by a commercial driver training school in accordance
18 with the pilot program established by the Division, a prospective licensee must
19 appear in person at a Division office to be photographed and present required
20 documentation. The Division shall update its appointment system to provide
21 appropriate appointment availability for purposes of the pilot program.
22 (6) For each type of drivers licensing – graduated, regular drivers, and
23 commercial drivers – the Division shall develop a plan for informing
24 prospective licensees about required examinations that will be administered
25 by commercial driver training schools through the pilot program.
26 (7) The Division shall maintain complete oversight over administration of
27 examinations by commercial driver training schools participating in the pilot
28 program, including providing schools with training, guidelines, and materials
29 required to administer examinations in accordance with Division standards.
30 (8) The Division must take prompt and appropriate remedial action against any
31 participating commercial driver training school that fails to comply with
32 Division standards or applicable State and federal requirements.
33 SECTION 43.19.(b) The Division shall report its plan for implementation of the
34 pilot program outlined in subsection (a) of this section to the Joint Legislative Transportation
35 Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division no later than April 1, 2026. The report
36 shall include an examination of the anticipated costs of implementing the pilot program, the
37 number of anticipated participating licensed commercial driver training schools in selected
38 counties, and any recommendations or legislative proposals related to the proposed pilot
39 program.
40 SECTION 43.19.(c) Nothing in this section shall limit any authorization set forth in
41 Article 14 of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes.
42 SECTION 43.19.(d) The Division shall implement the pilot program on January 1,
43 2027. No later than January 1, 2029, the Division shall submit a report to the Joint Legislative
44 Transportation Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division evaluating the
45 effectiveness of the pilot program in improving the drivers licensing process and any
46 recommendations related to extending, expanding, or terminating the program. The pilot program
47 shall terminate on July 1, 2029.
