47 UNIT PRICING COST
48 SECTION 43.22. G.S. 136-18.05(b)(1a) reads as rewritten:
49 "(1a) Efficiency. – The Department shall adopt procedures in all stages of the
50 construction process to streamline project delivery, including consolidating
51 environmental review processes, expediting multiagency reviews,
Page 510 Senate Bill 257-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 accelerating right-of-way acquisitions, and pursuing design build and other
2 processes to collapse project stages. By December 1, 2015, the Department
3 shall establish a baseline unit pricing structure for transportation goods used
4 in highway maintenance and construction projects and set annual targets for
5 three years based on its unit pricing. In forming the baseline unit prices and
6 future targets, the Department shall collect data from each Highway Division
7 on its expenditures on transportation goods during the 2015-2016 fiscal year.
8 based upon a rolling average of the three previous fiscal years. Beginning
9 January 1, 2016, no Highway Division shall exceed a ten percent (10%)
10 variance over a baseline unit price set for that year in accordance with this
11 subdivision. The Department of Transportation shall institute annual tracking
12 to monitor pricing variances. The ten percent (10%) maximum variance set
13 under this subdivision is intended to account for regional differences requiring
14 varying product mixes. If a Highway Division exceeds the unit pricing
15 threshold, the Department shall submit a report to the Joint Legislative
16 Transportation Oversight Committee, the Fiscal Research Division of the
17 General Assembly, the chairs of the House of Representatives Appropriations
18 Committee on Transportation, and the chairs of the Senate Appropriations
19 Committee on the Department of Transportation no later than the fifteenth day
20 of February following the end of the calendar year on why the variance
21 occurred and what steps are being taken to bring the Highway Division back
22 into compliance. In order to drive savings, unit pricing may be reduced
23 annually as efficiencies are achieved."
